<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Lawyers Accuse Opposition for Creating Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 550 lawyers in the
country Monday accused the opposition for creating "an unnecessary
controversy" centering the recent comment of the prime minister on
granting of bails to criminals.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said in a statement that a certain political
quarter is collecting signature for contempt petition against
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina. According to the law of the country,
only a court can draw such contempt proceedings, the lawyers
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hasina recently said that the judiciary should be
accountable as criminals are repeating crimes after obtaining
bails from courts.
</P>
<P>
The statement observed that the prime minister's comment was
the manifestation of people's concerns in the wake of growing
criminal activities and it deserved a healthy discussion involving
all concerned.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the signature campaign under the
auspices of political parties was, in fact, a political and party
campaign.
</P>
<P>
"The people will never want that any lawyer or member of
parliament would do anything which would encourage in creating
conflict between the judiciary and the executive," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition lawmakers will file a contempt petition
with the High Court against Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina for her
remarks against the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
All the MPs of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), Jatiya
Party and the Jamaat-e-Islami will be plaintiff in the petition,
BNP secretary General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan told newsmen Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have unanimously decided to file the
petition to protect the judiciary and ensure rule of law in the
country, Bhuiyan said, adding as lawmakers "we can not sit idle
when the government and the prime minister attempt to destroy the
judicial system."
</P>
<P>
BNP alone has 110 MPs in the 330-seat parliament. The petition
may be filed on Wednesday, according to opposition sources.
</P>
<P>
Over three hundred lawyers of High Court have already signed a
statement to file a separate contempt petition against the prime
minister for her remarks on judiciary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
