<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to See Trade Surplus of 9.7 Billion Dollars This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's government-run
economic research institute Monday predicted the country's trade
surplus to be some 9.7 billion U.S. dollars this year, less than
the official estimate.
</P>
<P>
The (South) Korea Institute of Economics and Trade said in a
report that due to increase in imports, the country's trade
surplus would drop to around 5.3 billion dollars in the second
half of this year, bringing down the surplus total.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Ministry of Commerce, Industry and Energy
estimated the trade surplus totals 10 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The institute put second-half exports at 90.7 billion dollars,
up 16.8 percent from the same period last year, and compared the
figure with 83 billion dollars in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, chiefly as a result of increased international oil
prices, the country's imports would grow by 30.5 percent to 85.4
billion dollars in the second half, raising this year's imports
total to 164 billion, up 37 percent from 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
