<HEADLINE> Six Egyptian Parents Arrested for Helping Children Cheat on Exam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Six Egyptian parents have been
arrested for helping their children cheat on a secondary school
placement exam, an official of the Education Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
About 50 parents gathered near the Dar el-Salam school in the
southern city of Sohag, where their children were taking the exam,
said Mustafa Mohamed Mustafa, undersecretary of state for education
and teaching.
</P>
<P>
A number of them entered the school and shouted out answers to
the questions being asked by the teachers, Mustafa was quoted as
saying by the country's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Police moved in and arrested the six, while others managed to
flee, he added.
</P>
<P>
The report said that it is a common practice at exam time but
only came to light after Mustafa was called in by the examination
jury to deal with the problem. A commission has been set up to
study whether to annul the Sohag examination results because of
fraud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
