<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament to Hold Another Special Session on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Knesset, or
Parliament, decided Tuesday afternoon to call another special
meeting during the summer recess to discuss the possible renewal
of the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Knesset session, which itself was a special session in
the summer recess beginning on August 2, made the decision after 39
legislators voted for the motion, while only one Knesset member
voted against it.
</P>
<P>
The agenda for the next special meeting, according to Israeli
Channel 3 Television reports, will include the opposition parties'
charges against Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on the legality
of his government, his negotiating behavior in the peace talks, his
continuing talks with the Palestinians without a Knesset majority.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's control in the 120-member Knesset had
shrunk from a 68-majority to a 40-minority following a series of
resignations by his ruling partners over talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's session, Ariel Sharon, chairman of the leading
opposition Likud party, accused Barak of surrendering Israeli soils
in the talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to a proposal submitted during last month's
Camp David talks, in which Israel will exchange lands with the
Palestinians for annexing some settlements in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The 15-day-long summit talks, attended by Barak, U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, failed to reach
any agreement in the end.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, there are reports that the three leaders may hold
another three-way summit in New York when they attends the upcoming
United Nations Millennium Summit there at the beginning of next
month.
</P>
<P>
However, Likud faction whip Reuven Rivlin reiterated Tuesday
that the Knesset should bar Barak from continuing talks with the
Palestinians as long as he did not have a majority in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that he is planning to garner signatures of 61
lawmakers in favor of a plenary session of the Knesset on August
28.
</P>
<P>
At the end of such a plenary meeting, Rivlin hoped, a regulation
stipulating that the prime minister cannot sign any agreement
without the support of a majority of the Knesset could be passed.
</P>
<P>
Rivlin threatened that if Knesset Speaker Avraham Burg does not
permit this special meeting, he will consider petitioning Israel's
High Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Defending the government, Immigrant Absorption Minister Yuli
Tamir said that in her opinion, there is no question over Barak's
legal power to continue the Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, she added, was directly elected by Israeli
people by a large margin and when he finishes an agreement with
Arafat, he will surely bring it to a referendum as he had promised.
</P>
<P>
The people will judge his achievement in the referendum, the
minister concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
