<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Attorney-General Rules Barak's Appointments Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Attorney-General
Elyakim Rubinstein ruled Tuesday that Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
appointment of ministers and parliament members as acting ministers
is legal, even if they are returning to the portfolios they
resigned earlier.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was made in response to a complaint filed by Knesset
(parliament) member Limor Livnat from the opposition Likud faction
against Barak's appointments and questioned the legality of them.
</P>
<P>
Livnat had objected to the appointments of Ra'anan Cohen from
the ruling One Israel bloc as Minister of Labor and Social Affairs,
and Roni Milo from Center Party as Health Minister, without the
approval of the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
She had also objected to the anticipated return of the left-wing
Meretz party to the ministries of education, trade and industry,
and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
A representative for the attorney general responded to Livnat's
objections in a letter. Rubinstein conceded that the situation is
problematic and undesirable. However, he said that it does not go
against the law.
</P>
<P>
The attorney added that the law authorizes the prime minister to
make appointments, which do not need Knesset approval, as long as
they are for a period of less than one year.
</P>
<P>
Barak is scheduled to meet Meretz leader Yossi Sarid Tuesday
evening on the possibility of having the party back into the
government. Three Meretz ministers resigned in June at the height
of a government crisis triggered by Sarid's disputes with the
ultra-Orthodox Shas Party over funding for the powerful religious
party's educational network.
</P>
<P>
Sarid, the former education minister, has expressed the
willingness to rejoin the government but on conditions that he
returns to the education portfolio with full authority over the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Barak has filled up posts vacated by such former
coalition partners as Israeli Ba'aliya (Russian Immigrants' Party),
the National Religious Party and Shas Party, and later by former
Foreign Minister David Levy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
