<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., British Jets Bomb Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said that the U.S. and
British warplanes bombed its northern part on Tuesday, but reported
no damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
an Iraqi military spokesman said that at 11:20 local time (0720
GMT), seven formations of the U.S. and British planes carried out
14 armed sorties over the three northern provinces of Dohuk,
Neiveva and Erbil.
</P>
<P>
The planes bombed "civilian and service installations" in the
area, the spokesman said, adding that Iraqi gunners opened fire at
the aggressing planes and forced them to flee back to their bases
in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British jets have been enforcing the so-called no-fly
zone in northern Iraq, imposed after the 1991 Gulf War with the
claimed aim of protecting the region's Kurdish population.
</P>
<P>
A similar air exclusion zone was also set up in southern Iraq to
allegedly protect the Shiite Muslims there and is patrolled by U.S.
and British aircraft based in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad does not recognize the zones, which are not authorized
by any specific United Nations resolution, and has regularly fired
on aircraft patrolling them since the joint U.S.-British air
strikes against Iraq in December 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
