<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Meets Japanese MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
said on Tuesday Jordan is keen to strengthen relations with Japan,
the largest creditor to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah made the remarks in a meeting with visiting Japanese
parliamentarian and President of the Japan-Jordan Parliamentary
Friendship Association Koichi Kato.
</P>
<P>
The monarch commended assistance provided by Japan in the
development process of Jordan as well as its efforts to promote
peace in the Middle East region, Jordan's official news agency
Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the role played by the Japan-Jordan
Parliamentary Association in boosting relations between the two
countries in all fields, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kato expressed satisfaction over the status quo of
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also lauded King Abdullah's efforts in establishing a just,
durable and comprehensive peace in the region as well as his
efforts to develop national economy and to achieve sustainable
development at home, Petra said.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Abdullah bestowed upon Kato the independence
medal of the first order in appreciation of his contribution to
promoting friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kato arrived here on Monday for a two-day friendly visit to
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting on Tuesday, Jordanian Foreign Minister
Abdel Ilah al-Khatib told Kato that Jordan attaches importance to
developing ties with Japan, and the kingdom appreciates Japan's
efforts to promote peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Currently Japan is the largest creditor to Jordan and some 1.9
billion U.S. dollars out of Jordan's 6.9 billion dollars of foreign
debts are owed to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japanese laws prohibit the government from writing off debts for
another country, but part of the debts owed by Jordan are likely to
be converted into Japanese investments into the kingdom. 
</P>
