<HEADLINE> Iran's Journalists Association Criticizes Press Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Association of Journalists
on Tuesday strongly criticized the crackdown on pro-reform
newspapers and journalists by the country's conservative judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Terming the "restrictions and hardships" exerted on journalists
as unprecedented in Iran's history, the association demanded the
Majlis (parliament) to take measures to safeguard press freedom,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Majlis members should move to prevent the illegal bans on
newspapers and safeguard the freedom of expression, the association
said in an open letter to the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly protest the manner in which journalists are treated
and plead for justice," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The association urged the Majlis to stand firmly, with its legal
mechanisms, against the blatant disrespect of journalists' rights.
</P>
<P>
Iran's conservative judiciary has for the past few months
ordered the closure of over 20 pro-reform newspapers and journals
on the so-called charges of defamation, violating Islamic values
and propagating pro-American reforms. A number of reformist
journalists have also been imprisoned on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
The move came after President Mohammad Khatami's reformist
allies won an overwhelming victory over their conservative
opponents in February's Majlis election.
</P>
<P>
Iran's reformist-controlled Majlis, which replaced its
conservative predecessor on May 27, has tried to remove the
restrictive clauses in the press law, the basis for the
conservative crackdown on reformist papers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
But on August 6, a scheduled debate on the press law in the
Majlis was cancelled on the order of supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, the highest authority of the country who is believed to
stand by the conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
