<HEADLINE> SADC to Facilitate Implementation of Trade Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Committee of Ministers of
Trade for the Southern African Development Community (SADC) has
considered and approved all necessary documentation to facilitate
implementation of its free trade protocol on September 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Briefing a press conference here on Tuesday, Zambian Minister
of Commerce, Trade and Industry William Harrington said 11 of the
14 member states, namely Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe, will join this arrangement first.
</P>
<P>
The SADC Trade Protocol was signed at the Heads of State summit
in August 1996 in Maseru, Lesotho. By the time when the Windhoek
summit was held on August 4, 2000 in Namibia, 10 of the 11 member
states that are party to this protocol had ratified it. Zambia is
the only country that has yet to ratify.
</P>
<P>
With the two-thirds majority that is required to enforce the
protocol already attained, the minister said, it should have come
into force on January 25, 2000. However, the implementation
process could not be effected due to the fact that negotiations
were still on-going.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia, on its part, had not been in a comfortable
position to consider the ratification prior to the recent SADC
Trade Minister Retreat in the Tanzanian capital Dar-es-Salaam, due
to a number of unresolved issues.
</P>
<P>
The Dar-es-Salaam Retreat afforded Zambia the opportunity to
resolve several of the outstanding issues, which include the rules
of origin, dispute settlement mechanism, elimination of non-tariff
barriers, treatment of sensitive products and market access on
sugar, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Zambia is fully committed to
implementing the trade protocol scheduled for September 1 and its
current position does not in any way imply that the country is not
committed to seeing the process through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
