<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Lawyers Demonstrate for Rule of Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- About 100 members of the Law
Society of Zimbabwe Tuesday staged a peaceful demonstration to
force the government to restore the rule of law on commercial
farms invaded by war veterans.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers marched to the parliament building in Harare where
they delivered the petition to Speaker Emmerson Mnangagwa who was
expected to hand it over to President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
"We are apolitical and not opposed to land reform, but this has
to be done in a legal and orderly manner," President of the Law
Society Sternford Moyo told the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Law Society has appealed to the responsible authorities on
many occasions to restore the rule of law but in vain, Moyo said,
citing a recent letter to the new Home Affairs Minister John Nkomo
to discuss the issue but there was no response.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed with the commitment of the government to
restore the rule of law," he said. "The matter does not appear to
have enjoyed the urgency which it deserves."
</P>
<P>
Thousands of war veterans have invaded about 1,500 white-owned
commercial farms to force the government to speed up its land
resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
The government has recently started a fast-track land
resettlement program aimed at resettling landless people. 
</P>
