<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans Urged to Conserve Natural resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Executive Director of the
Environment 2000 Foundation of Zimbabwe Charlene Hewat Tuesday
called on war veterans occupying farms and other people being
resettled under the government's fast-track land redistribution
program to conserve natural resources.
</P>
<P>
She was quoted by the Zimbabwe News Agency as saying that there
had been wanton destruction of trees on occupied farms and this
would have disastrous consequences on future generations.
</P>
<P>
"It is disastrous," she said. "Trees are the lungs of the earth
and by destroying them we are destroying our future generations."
</P>
<P>
She urged those on occupied farms and those having been
resettled to use the land sustainably without rampant destruction
of trees.
</P>
<P>
There was need for proper planning and implementation of the
land redistribution program to avoid further depletion of the
forests, she said, adding that "it is unfortunate they are looking
at the short-term benefits but in the long-term we must conserve
our trees."
</P>
<P>
According to Hewat, the Environment 2000 Foundation had met
several times with the national leadership of the former
liberation war fighters urging them to advise their members to
desist from cutting down trees, but the situation had not improved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an environment program officer was quoted as saying
that it was difficult to source funds for environmental management
programs for people on occupied farms because "there is no
documentation from the government and everything is being done
haphazardly."
</P>
<P>
Farm occupations which started in February this year had been
blamed for exacerbating the extent of environmental damage.
</P>
