<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Lifts Week-Long Suspension of Aid Flights in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-
General Kofi Annan announced here Tuesday that the world body will
resume aid flights to the Sudan, lifting a week-long suspension
that followed a spate of government bomb attacks on relief
aircraft and compounds.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was contained in a statement issued here by
Annan's spokesman. The Sudanese government has given the United
Nations assurances that it will be safe to fly.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general is pleased to announce that tomorrow,
August 16, 2000, the United Nations will resume all humanitarian
relief flights throughout the Sudan," the statement said. "He
welcomes that he received from the president of the Republic of
the Sudan that all measures are being taken to ensure the safety
of Operation Lifeline Sudan personnel and aircraft."
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general trusts that the government of the Sudan
and other parties to the conflict will continue to honor fully
their commitment to ensure the safety and security of relief
workers and also the vulnerable populations whose urgent needs U.N.
humanitarian personnel are trying to address throughout the
country," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led relief effort, the Operation Lifeline Sudan,
suspended flights on August 8 after some 18 bombs were dropped
near a U.N. aircraft in the southern town of Mapel.
</P>
<P>
The attack followed a dramatic escalation o bomb strikes on
rebel-held towns in the southern Sudan by government warplanes.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 2 million people have been killed in the conflict
and related famines. Millions are dependent on relief supplies
from aid agencies which fly daily to dozens of locations to drop
or distribute food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
