<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecstasy Seizures in Canada Almost Double Last Year's Haul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian police have seized 712,
000 tablets of the designer drug Ecstasy this year, almost
doubling the entire haul for 1999, the Ottawa Citizen reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The seizures of the "feel-good" tablets, with a street value up
to 28.5 million Canadian dollars (about 19.2 million U.S. dollars),
illustrate demand for the drug has exploded from last year's haul
of just 360,000 tablets, which were valued up to 14.4 million
Canadian dollars (about 9.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The growing demand for the drug has caused two major problems.
One is that drug producing labs are threatening to shift from
their traditional bases in Europe to Canada.
</P>
<P>
There are no estimates as to the number of labs, but there
appears to be no shortage, according to Det. Randy Smith of the
Toronto police major drug unit.
</P>
<P>
Each investigation conducted by the Toronto police this year
has turned up a lab, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is that drug producers are increasingly
targeting easy prey of teens.
</P>
<P>
In Canada's most populous province of Ontario, about 4.8
percent of junior and high school students have used the drug in
the past 12 months, said a study by the Center for Addiction and
Mental Health in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
Police say that they are getting better at investigating
Ecstasy operations whether it involves rings that import the drug
into the country, or labs that manufacture the drug in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Ecstasy's popularity is largely based on the widely-held belief
that it has no negative side effects. But researchers have warned
that more use has meant more Ecstasy related deaths.
</P>
<P>
Research is beginning to detail the depression or hangover that
can occur a few days following an Ecstasy high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
