<HEADLINE> Prices For Germany's UMTS Licenses Keep Soaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Bidders for license to build
Germany's future mobile system Tuesday offered a total sum of 83.3
billion Deutsche marks (38.6 billion U.S. dollars) as the auction
on the Universal Mobile Telecommunication System (UMTS), is
approaching the end.
</P>
<P>
In the 148th round, there are still six consortiums, one fewer
than at the start, vying for 12 frequency blocks in auction in
Frankfurt held by the German telecommunication authorities.
</P>
<P>
There are speculations that one more bidder will soon quit,
which leaves enough blocks for the remaining ones to end the
competition, probably by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
The UMTS, which offers a data-transporting speech 200 times
more than the currently used GSM, or Global System of Mobile,
phones, enables customers to enjoy multi-media functions,
including Internet-surfing on mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Hans Eichel has made it clear that
expected billions of proceeds from the UMTS auction will go to
debt reduction. But opposition parties have called for part of the
income to be used in alleviating the tax burden of ordinary
families.
</P>
<P>
The 80-some billion DM (37.1 billion dollars) is four times as
much as what was originally expected by Eichel, who said that in
case that 20 billion DM (9.3 billion dollars) is committed to
slashing Germany's national debt, the federal government can save
1 billion DM (0.46 billion dollars) in interest payment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
