<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Panel to Probe Illicit Exploitation of Minerals in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Five experts led by a
former minister of energy from Cote d'Ivoire, Safiatou Ba-N'Daw,
have been appointed to probe how diamonds and other natural
resources are illegally exploited to fuel a many-sided conflict in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), the United Nations said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the president of the U.N. Security Council, U.
N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that Ba-N'Daw will head the
Nairobi-based panel, which is appointed for six months.
</P>
<P>
Annan described the former minister, who is also a former
official of the World Bank, as "an eminent person whose experience
amply qualifies her to occupy this important position."
</P>
<P>
The other four members of the panel are Francis Ekoko of
Cameroon, Moustapha Tall of Senegal, Henri Maire of Switzerland,
and Mel Holt of the United States, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The appointment must be confirmed by the Security Council,
which asked Annan in the June 2 resolution to recommend names.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that the panel will "convene in New York for an
initial briefing period before proceeding to Nairobi, which would
serve as the basis of their operations."
</P>
<P>
The decision to look into illegal trade in mineral resources in
the DRC is modeled upon the council's investigation of breaches of
U.N. sanctions against the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Fighting in the DRC, the former Zaire, has been going on since
August 1998. The government of President Laurent Kabila, backed by
Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe, is battling rebel groups supported
by Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The DRC panel will "follow up on reports and collect
information on all activities of illegal exploitation of natural
resources and other forms of wealth," the council resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said that the panel will "research and analyze
the links between the exploitation of the natural resources and
other forms of wealth in the DRC and the continuation of the
conflict." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
