<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Promotes Police Reform in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. official
Tuesday said that the U.N. Mission in Bosnia and Herzegovina (
UNMIBH) promoted police reform there through cutting down on the
allowed police strength by some 1,000 to 10,600 because of the
reduced needs in some areas of the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Miyet, U.N. under-secretary-general for peacekeeping,
told an open Security Council meeting that the police reduction
was made "because of the introduction of the State Border Service
and reduced needs in some of the smaller Federation cantons."
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the U.N. drive to achieve police
restructuring, police reform and the strengthening of the common
institutions in the police sector, which was identified by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in his report to the Security Council
as the main priorities for the U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, registration of police officers continues and since
June 2, 2000, more than 2,800 additional officers have been
registered," he said. "The mission is on track to conclude the
registration process by mid-December 2000 resulting in the first
transplant and comprehensive Law Enforcement Personnel Registry in
Bosnia and Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
"In parallel to the registration of the current police officers,
UNMIBH continues to assist local authorities in fulfilling their
obligation to ensure an adequate minority representation in their
police forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
The steps included the recruitment of minority cadets for the
police academies, voluntary redeployment of serving minority
officers between entities, and the encouragement for the displaced
and refugees for police officers to return to their pre-war homes
and rejoin local police forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In total, nearly 450 minority officers are currently attending
or have graduated from the two academies and 130 minority officers
have been identified for redeployment across entity lines," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"To promote police reform, UNMIBH has continued its efforts to
institute police commissioners in the Federation police, in order
to create a professional, nonpartisan, civil service-type
leadership for the police and insulate it from the direct
political influence of the Ministry of the Interior," Miyet said.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, the Security Council adopted a resolution to
authorize a 12-month extension of the UNMIBH, which comprises the
International Police Task Force and the Stabilization Force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
The International Police Task Force monitors, trains and
assists local police in Bosnia, where refugees have often
encountered hostilities when trying to return home in areas that
were "ethnically cleansed" during the 1992-1995 conflict involving
Moslems, Croats and Serbs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
