<HEADLINE> Turkey Sues Jerry-Contractors Over Last Summer's Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A total of 122 dossiers regarding
the contractors of the jerry-buildings that collapsed in Turkey's
western Izmit city and its Golcuk township in the deadly earthquake
on August 17, 1999, were sent on Tuesday to the Basic Criminal
Courts.
</P>
<P>
The republican prosecutors were conducting investigations into
the contractors of 392 and 534 cheesy buildings that broke down
respectively in Izmit and Golcuk in the devastating earthquake,
Anatolia News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors have so far completed the probe into contractors
of 70 ropy buildings in Izmit and 52 in Golcuk, requesting
imprisonment terms between four and 10 years for the jerry-
contractors.
</P>
<P>
Owners of those dwellings, which were heavily or moderately
damaged in the quake but where nobody died, had filed lawsuits in
the Fourth Basic Civil Court to get compensations from the jerry-
builders.
</P>
<P>
The devastating quake, measuring 7.4 degrees on the open-ended
Richter scale, rocked Turkey's northwestern Marmara Region on
August 17, 1999, claiming 16,899 lives and injuring 23,781 people,
according to official figures. The high casualties were blamed on
poor quality of buildings.
</P>
<P>
In Izmit and its Golcuk township, the epicenter of the quake,
most buildings were demolished as if they had been made of
cardboards.
</P>
<P>
On November 12, 1999, another 7.2-magnitude earthquake hit the
northwestern Bolu province, claiming hundreds of lives.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is an earthquake-prone country. After the two deadly
earthquakes, the government has put strict emphasis on quality of
buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
