<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Turn Bone Marrow Into Nerve Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. research team has
successfully coaxed bone marrow cells into becoming nerve cells,
raising the tantalizing possibility of an easily accessible source
of replacement cells to treat brain and nerve injuries and
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the August issue of Journal of Neuroscience Research,
the team of researchers at the University of Medicine and
Dentistry of New Jersey said they had developed a culture that
makes stem cells, the so-called body master cells that have the
potential to develop into any types of cells, turn into nerve
cells "like wildfire."
</P>
<P>
In their study, the researchers removed stem cells from the
bone marrow of rats and of humans and grew them in the laboratory
in shallow dishes. The cells normally would develop into tendon,
cartilage, muscle and fat.
</P>
<P>
Then they added an antioxidant, beta mercaptoethanol that had
been shown to help neurons live and grow, and some growth factors
such as fibroblast growth factor.
</P>
<P>
It turned out that 80 percent of the cells were converted into
neurons, said Dr. Ira Black, the leading scientist of the study.
</P>
<P>
Black and colleagues then transplanted the rat nerve cells to
the brains and spinal cords of rats and found that they survived,
for months so far.
</P>
<P>
Next they will test the cells in animals with Alzheimer's,
stroke, Parkinson's disease and spinal cord injuries. And experts
emphasized that huge amount of work needed to be done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Rises 0.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. industrial production
increased 0.4 percent in July from June despite a big drop in
electric utility output caused by unseasonably mild weather, the
Federal Reserve reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 0.4 percent increase, following a 0.2 percent gain in June,
was in line with what many analysts had expected and provided
evidence that manufacturing continues to rebound from last year's
sluggish performance. It was the fourth straight monthly advance
for output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output increased 0.5 percent in July, and mining
output rose 1.7 percent. Output at utilities, which dropped 2.5
percent in June, fell 3.3 percent last month as abnormally cool
weather in the east kept electricity generation down.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, industrial production in July was up 5.
8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report also said the nation's industries were operating
at 82.3 percent of capacity, up from 82.2 percent in June. The
capacity rate suggests an absence of production bottlenecks that
could cause shortages and higher prices.
</P>
<P>
There were other declining sectors in July, the Fed report
showed. Output of consumer goods fell 0.5 percent, led by durable
goods. Production of automotive products dropped 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The declines appeared to be in line with other recent data
suggesting a slowdown in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Fed has boosted interest rates six times over the past 14
months in an effort to slow the economy and keep inflation in
check. Many economists believe the Fed will leave rates unchanged
at its meeting next Tuesday, preferring to wait and see whether
the rate increases it has already approved will be enough to do
the job. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
