<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Expresses Concern Over KFOR Seizure of Serb Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government Tuesday
expressed "profound concern"over the Monday closure of a Serb
lead smelter in the flashpoint Kosovo town of Mitrovica forced by
the United Nations mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The plant, part of the Trepca mining and metals group in
Mitrovica that is divided into the Serb-dominated north and the
Albanian-held south, was occupied by the multinational
peacekeeping force in Kosovo (KFOR) and the police units of the U.
N. mission in the Yugoslav province early Monday.
</P>
<P>
Such an action represents "an attempt to capture and estrange"
property that the U.N. mission does not own, the Interfax news
agency quoted a Foreign Ministry statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
There is "obviously a political motivation behind ... the
arbitrary seizure of the Trepca plant" without agreement of the
plant's legitimate owner, the Republic of Serbia, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
It regarded the U.N. argument to justify the move as "holding
no water." Some U.N. officials have said that the smelter gives
off lead 200 times above the safe level into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The action taken by the U.N. mission in Kosovo and the U.N.
Secretary General's special envoy there, Bernard Kushner, has
manifested "their inability to solve problems... through political
dialogue," said the Foreign Ministry in the statement.
</P>
<P>
It also stressed the fact that more than 2,000 people, mostly
Serbs, were employed at the plant, one of the few businesses
continuing to operate in Kosovo after the launch of the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Russian Foreign Ministry
criticized Kushner for "forcing elections" in the Yugoslav
province this year "at any cost."
</P>
<P>
Such an approach will undermine efforts towards a truly
democratic state in Kosovo, the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Kushner has decided to hold municipal elections on October 28
despite Russia's objections, the statement said, adding that it
will not support any election in Kosovo this year since not even
minimal conditions exist for a truly free, fair and democratic
election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
