<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuation Underway for Sunken Russian Submarine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev said Tuesday that evacuation of the 116 servicemen aboard
the stranded "Kursk" submarine has started in the Barents Sea as
weather improves.
</P>
<P>
The storm in the area of the accident has calmed down, which
makes it possible to carry out the rescue operation, the Interfax
news agency quoted Sergeyev as saying.
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose "Kursk" went down to the bottom of the
Barents Sea on Sunday while attending a routine exercise of the
Russian Northern Fleet. It is not yet clear whether there are any
casualties inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
Russian Navy spokesman Igor Dygalo said the evacuation work
might last 6 to 7 hours, although "it is never possible to
forecast the situation because of the changing weather, poor
visibility and powerful underwater currents."
</P>
<P>
The cause of the accident remains unknown and all
possibilities are being checked, Sergeyev said. He listed
collision with another object or an explosion in the first
compartment of the submarine as among the most probable scenarios.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were two U.S. submarines nearby at
the time of the accident, which reported sound of an explosion.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk", with a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and
able to dive to an depth of up to 500 meters, was commissioned for
the Russian Navy in 1995. It is armed with torpedoes and "Granite"
cruise missiles. Earlier Interfax reports said the submarine can
operate autonomously for up to 120 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
