<HEADLINE> Border Guards Patrolling With Help of Networking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Patrolling part of China's
northwestern border is no longer done with soldiers riding on
horses, but by using patrol cars armed with high-tech equipment
like computers, wireless transmitters, GPS devices and video
cameras.
</P>
<P>
Commanders of the border troops in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region can easily monitor the situation on the border
area from hundreds of kilometers away as the patrol cars send back
all the information about the movements there.
</P>
<P>
The border troops getting on line with the People's Liberation
Army (PLA) information network shows that the army has entered
into a new stage of automated patrolling, according to military
experts.
</P>
<P>
Recently, border units of the Yili sub-commanding area of the
PLA invested millions of yuan to develop the automated patrolling
system and so far, all the local border troops have connected them
with the PLA information network center. 
</P>
