<HEADLINE> Barak Pledges Further Peace Efforts, Calls Russian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said on Tuesday that Israel will push ahead its peace-making
efforts with the Palestinians, but will not rush for peace at any
price.
</P>
<P>
Touring the southern town of Eshkolot, Barak said even if Israel
cannot find a sincere peace partner in the peace process, it still
can win international support for its efforts, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
He noted Israel will continue its peace efforts, but will not
strive for peace at any price.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Barak held a telephone conversation with
Russian President Vladimir Putin. The Prime Minister's Office said
Barak got the impression that Russia does not support a unilateral
declaration of statehood by the Palestinians before the September
13 deadline for a final peace between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Russian leader conveyed the same stance last week in a
meeting with Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Prime Minister's Office was quoted by the
radio report as saying the Russian stance is of great importance,
viewing the traditional pro-Arab positions that the Russians have
taken.
</P>
<P>
The stance, said the official, again showed that Israel's
worldwide diplomatic efforts aimed at explaining the country's
stance on the peace talks are successful.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders hoped to hold talks while attending the U.N.
millenium summit in New York slated for September.
</P>
<P>
Barak also offered to help rescue the Russian nuclear-powered
submarine stranded on the Arctic seabed with more than 100 sailors
on board. Putin said the submarine is in serious conditions and the
chances to rescue the sailors are quite slim.
</P>
<P>
Barak called Putin last Thursday prior to Arafat's visit to
Russia to update him on the developments of the Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Following the failure of last month's Camp David summit, both
the Palestinians and Israelis launched an extensive information
campaign to drum up international support for their positions in
the peace talks. 
</P>
