<HEADLINE> Estrada's Net Approval Rating Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The approval rating of Philippine
President Joseph Estrada has gone up to 53 percent mainly due to
his handling of the Mindanao conflict, according to the results of
a nationwide survey released Tuesday by Pulse Asia Inc.
</P>
<P>
Felipe Miranda of Pulse Asia said in a statement that in their
latest survey, President Estrada got an approval rating of 53
percent, as compared to a disapproval rating of 26 percent, or a
net approval rating of +27 points.
</P>
<P>
The Pulse Asia survey, conducted July 14-28 with 1,200
respondents, showed an increase of six percent in Estrada's net
approval rating, as against the figures collated and interpreted
by the poll body in March this year which gave him a net approval
rating of +21 points.
</P>
<P>
Miranda said the improved rating was mainly due to Estrada's
handling of the crisis situation in Mindanao, including the
hostage-taking by the Abu Sayyaf and the armed conflict between
government troops and the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front.
According to Miranda, this was clearly reflected in the survey
results from Mindanao that showed President Estrada's approval
rating had gone up to 62 percent, compared to a disapproval rating
of only 17 percent, or a net approval rating of +41 points.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada's net approval rating in Mindanao was +28
points in March.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the president's net approval rating also
improved significantly in Metro Manila, from -6 points in March to
+27 points in July.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada's highest net approval rating of +65 points
was recorded in May 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
