<HEADLINE> Manila Denies Issuing Shoot-to-Kill Order on MILF Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
clarified Tuesday that it has not issued a shoot-to-kill order
against Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) chairman Hashim
Salamat, vice-chairman for military affairs Al Haj Murad and MILF
spokesman Ed Kabalu.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Secretary Alfredo Lim of the Department
of Interior and Local Government explained that the only directive
issued by his office involving the three MILF leaders was for law
enforcers to gather information that could lead to their arrest.
</P>
<P>
Lim announced earlier that the government is offering a total
of 9 million pesos (225,000 U.S. dollars) for information that
would lead to the arrest of the three top MILF leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I have not issued any shoot-to-kill order. I don't understand
who is spreading those words," he said.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo Puno earlier
clarified that the directive issued was for the arrest of the
three MILF leaders, and that no instructions were issued to have
them killed on sight.
</P>
<P>
Puno stressed that the law enforcers were only instructed to
act accordingly should Salamat, Murad or Kabalu resist arrest.
</P>
<P>
Lim said should the MILF leaders decide to fight it out with
the police, "the police and the military have to defend themselves.
"
</P>
<P>
Kabalu earlier issued a statement that he would rather be
killed than surrender to the police, saying that he will "fight it
out to the end."
</P>
<P>
Reacting to this, Lim said the police and military officers
will have to act accordingly, should they come face to face with
Kabalu.
</P>
<P>
Lim said posters are being ready to provide the public the
exact description of the MILF leaders, so they could volunteer
information on their location. 
</P>
