<HEADLINE> Importance of Peace Highlighted on Anniversary of Japan's Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Several Japanese civic groups held
rallies in Tokyo Tuesday to pledge for peace and express their
opposition to cabinet ministers' visits to Yasukuni Shrine on the
55th anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 members of the Heiwa Izuokukai (group of bereaved
families of peace) held a meeting to discuss the current state of
Japan's war-renouncing Constitution.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the group members took to the streets and
marched near Yasukuni Shrine demanding that the prime minister and
cabinet members refrain from making official visits to the shrine
where 14 class-A war criminals, including Japan's wartime Prime
Minister Hideki Tojo, are enshrined.
</P>
<P>
Group member Itsuko Ishikawa, 67, stressed the importance of
speaking in concrete and accurate terms of the tragedy of war to
gain the understanding of young people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 200 people took part in a meeting sponsored by
the Forum Heiwa Jinken Kankyo (forum for peace, human rights, and
the environment) at the Chidorigafuchi cemetery in Tokyo's Chiyoda
Ward to offer a prayer for people killed in wars.
</P>
<P>
"We must not change our resolve to build peace on regret for
the past, and not resort to war," Takako Doi, chairwoman of the
opposition Social Democratic Party, told the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Japan's Constitution has been admired throughout
the world as a new benchmark for the 21st century, Doi stressed
that it is the duty of the citizens to preserve its Article 9,
which renounces war and the use of force as means of settling
international disputes. 
</P>
