<HEADLINE> Manila Doubts MILF's Sincerity to Talk Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
expressed doubts Tuesday over the sincerity and willingness of the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) to negotiate peace with the
government, following its withdrawal from the talks scheduled on
August 21 and 22.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Press Secretary told reporters here that there was
no connection between the peace talks and the reward being offered
by the government for any information that could lead to the
arrest of the three MILF leaders with outstanding warrants of
arrest.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Al Haj Murad, MILF vice-chairman for military affairs,
through a taped interview, reportedly called for the withdrawal of
the MILF from the peace talks because of the reward money offered
by the government for his capture as well as for the capture of
MILF Chairman Hashim Salamat and MILF Spokesman Eid Kabalu.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Alfredo Lim of the Department of the Interior and
Local Government has earlier announced that the government is
offering 9 million pesos (225,000 U.S. dollars) reward to anybody
who can give information that would lead to the capture of the
three MILF leaders.
</P>
<P>
Puno said the government regrets the decision of the MILF to
pull out from the talks, but stressed that the Muslim rebel group
has no right to cite as an argument, the reward offered against
Salamat, Murad and Kabalu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the three leaders with rewards on their heads are
not part of the MILF peace panel, as he stressed that safe conduct
passes have already been issued to those who were supposed to
participate in the talks from the MILF side.
</P>
<P>
Puno said that the government remains hopeful that the
negotiations will continue, adding that the government "remains
ready and willing to sit down and discuss further aspects of the
peace agreement with the MILF."
</P>
<P>
The 15,000-strong MILF has been fighting for an independent
state in Mindanao for more than two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
