<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Thai Economy Jitters With Little Risk of New Crisis By Yuan Li </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- With rising oil prices, a
weakened currency and a bearish stock market in scene, Thailand's
economy seems to have slipped back to the old hard days in 1997
and 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, since the macro-economic situation now is
significantly different from that which led to the crisis in mid-
1997, the country is not likely to experience a new round of
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's external debts hit 109 billion U.S. dollars in 1997
when it lost all of its foreign exchange reserves in the battle
with international speculators. People panicked, losing their
confidence in the Thai economy completely.
</P>
<P>
Capital flew out of the country at an incredible rate. The baht
went into a free-fall. Interest rates soared. Inflation ran out of
control.
</P>
<P>
But now, with around 30 billion dollars foreign reserves in
hand, the country has accumulated 9.6 billion dollars current
account surplus so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the oil prices rose to an all-time high, the
government is confident that inflation will not be pushed beyond
2 percent because of stable consumer-product prices.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1998 and for most of 1999, the baht was hovering
around 36 to 38 baht to a U.S. dollar, but it fell to 41.62
against the dollar on July 26, hitting a 10-month low.
</P>
<P>
Yet top Thai financial officials said they were comfortable
with the present foreign exchange rate which should help boost
exports, hinting that with an inflation rate below 2 percent this
year the Thai economy can tolerate the baht at 42 against the
dollar without sacrificing growth.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi insisted that
Thailand's economic growth this year will not fall below 5 percent
thanks to an improvement of the global economy, Thailand's
strengthening exports and the government's fiscal stimulus package.
</P>
<P>
The economy posted 5.2 percent growth in the first quarter,
halfway in the 4 to 6 percent annual range projected by the
central bank for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Exports remain a bright star in the economy, growing 30.4
percent in U.S. dollar terms in the first quarter year-on-year.
Manufacturing also grew across the board with rising exports and
stronger domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Strong global demand for computers helped put integrated
circuits and electronic parts at the top of Thai exports. Gains
were also shown in the auto, petrochemicals, steel, jewelry and
textile industries.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates, continued fiscal stimulus programs and
slight recovery in consumer confidence helped boost domestic
consumption, with department stores, car and motorcycle sales and
value-added tax collection all posting increases.
</P>
<P>
Auto sales grew 62.1 percent in the first quarter from the year
before due to stronger domestic demand. Private investment also
posted positive gains on higher car sales, capital goods imports
and cement sales.
</P>
<P>
All of these figures show that Thailand has come a long way
from where it was in 1997 and 1998. The question now is not
whether the economy will fall into a crisis again but how to
sustain the recovery.
</P>
<P>
Some factors are working against a sustainable recovery. A
prolonged slump in the stock market has made it virtually
impossible for companies to raise money. Meanwhile, credit has
continued to shrink. Banks are reluctant to lend given their 1.6
trillion baht (40 billion dollars) non-performing loans (NPLs).
</P>
<P>
Government debt accounts for 52 percent of the gross domestic
product. The current account, which has registered a surplus since
1998, could run into a deficit in 2002 if the high import trend
continues. Then the country will have a problem financing the
economy, given the 92.3 billion dollars external debts as of March.
</P>
<P>
But the most important factor affecting the market recently may
be the fears of a change of government at the next general
election, widely expected to be held in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch Phatra Securities Ltd, a major local financial
institution, urges the next government to address four key issues
to restore optimism in the Thai economy.
</P>
<P>
The first is a willingness to implement a well-planned fiscal
stimulus program in order to boost long-term productivity.
</P>
<P>
Next, the government should move ahead with the planned
privatization.
</P>
<P>
Third, the central bank's low-interest rate policy should
remain even if the baht declines to 43 or 44 baht to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the government should adopt a proactive
interventionist role in the debt-restructuring and liquidation
processes, which may involve the use of additional public funds.
Such a move would help accelerate the net NPLs reduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
