<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Chad Agree on Joint Border Patrols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Chad have agreed to
start joint patrols along their borders to stem the recurring
incidents of armed robbery on their communities, Nigerian press
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo was quoted as saying after
meeting his Chadian counterpart Idris Derby on Monday in Maiduguri,
capital of Nigeria's northeast Borno State, that the two countries
are determined to restore peace and tranquillity along their
borders.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries had co-existed peacefully over
several decades and they now resolved to restore full and cordial
relationship between them, Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
According to Obasanjo, they have also agreed to work in concert
for the full utilization of their resources, especially under the
auspices of the Lake Chad Commission, for the mutual benefit of
member countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting of the two leaders in the past three
weeks. The first one was held in Ndjamena, the capital of Chad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
