<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Tribunal Successful in Handling Criminals of Rwanda Genocide: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) has been successful in
apprehending and bringing into its custody 43 mostly high-ranking
individuals accused of being the architects and propellants of the
Rwandan genocide.
</P>
<P>
The individuals include Jean kambanda, Rwandan Prime Minister
and Head of Government during the 1994 genocide, 11 ministers in
his cabinet, senior political and media leaders, as well as
military commanders, ICTR Assistant Secretary-General and
Registrar Agwu Ukiwe Okali told a press conference here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda's sentencing on a plea of guilty was the first time in
history that an individual, let alone a former Head of Government,
had been punished for the crime of genocide by an international
court, Okali said while attending a workshop here held by the East
African Law Society.
</P>
<P>
Another achievement of the Rwanda tribunal with far-reaching
potential implications is its pioneering advocacy for the
development of restitutive justice for crimes against humanity and
war crimes, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Okali, the tribunal's achievement helps create
peace and national reconciliation in the Great Lake Region,
especially in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
He urged Africans to absorb and internalize the lessons of the
Rwandan genocide so as to ensure a crime of such nature and
proportions should never again occur.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, over half a million ethnic Tutsi and politically
moderate Hutus were massacred within a period of three months.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council adopted resolution 955 in
1994, which created the ICTR to bring to justice those responsible
for genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
