<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Consumer Market Keeps Upward Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China's consumer market
maintained its upward momentum for the first half of the year by
seeing higher growth in retail sales in July than the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
According to figures the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS)
released today, retail sales nationwide totaled 259.69 billion
yuan in July, up 9.1 percent on a year-on-year basis. The growth
rate was 0.2 percentage points higher than that in June and 3.5
percentage points higher than that a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, the NBS pointed out, the gap between the consumer
market in urban and rural areas remained big. July's retail sales
in cities soared 10.1 percent on an annual basis, while that in
rural areas grew by only 7.5 percent. In terms growth rate, the
rural market lagged behind the urban market by 2.6 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
But competition for market shares are intensifying.
</P>
<P>
According to the NBS, prices for telecommunication products,
cars and color TV sets have been repeatedly reduced over the past
few months, prompting faster growth of sales volume.
</P>
<P>
In July, prices of color TV sets saw an all-round decline, with
the prices of Chinese-made 29-inch color TVs falling below 2,000
yuan (240 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Increasing sales of seasonal commodities and promotional
campaigns by retail companies also helped invigorate the consumer
market, the bureau said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
