<HEADLINE> Australian Defense Force Urged to Work With Aid Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Defense Force (
ADF) would work with aid agencies and business in military
hotspots under a proposal put forward by defense chief Admiral
Chris Barrie on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barrie used a conference on the issue of food and water
security to flesh out an idea of recognizing the changing nature
of military operations.
</P>
<P>
He said the days of the army going in, enforcing the peace and
then departing are over.
</P>
<P>
He said the growing number of peacekeeping missions such as
those in East Timor and Bougainville showed that a more
sophisticated approach was required and this included nation
rebuilding actions.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that as our appreciation for the new framework for
security grows, governments will be more inclined to explore the
possibilities of creating a closer relationship and mission
between defense forces, aid organizations and development agencies,
" Barrie told the conference.
</P>
<P>
Under his idea, the ad hoc relationship between defense forces
and aid agencies would be formalized.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Democrats welcomed Barrie's comments and the
party's defense and foreign affairs spokeswoman said it was time
the ADF looked at its role as one different from soldiers fighting
conventional battles. 
</P>
