Sergeyev said Tuesday that an evacuation of the crew of the
stranded Kursk submarine has started in the Barents Sea as weather
improves.
</P>
<P>
The storm in the area of the accident has quieted down, which
makes it possible to carry out the rescue operation, the Interfax
news agency quoted Sergeyev as saying.
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose "Kursk" went down to the bottom of the
Barents Sea on Sunday while attending a routing exercise of the
Russian Northern Fleet. It is not clear whether there are any
casualties among more than 100 servicemen aboard the vessel.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the accident is still unknown and all versions
are being checked, Sergeyev said. He listed collision with a
different object or an explosion in the first compartment of the
submarine as among the most probable scenarios.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were two U.S. submarines nearby at
the time of the accident and they reported the sound of an
explosion.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk" was commissioned for the Russian Navy in 1995. It
has a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and can dive to depths of
up to 500 meters. The submarine is armed with torpedoes and "
Granite" cruise missiles. The vessel can operate autonomously for
up to 120 days and carries a 107-man crew, including 52 officers,
Interfax reported earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
