<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cement price in Egyptian market went down to 179
Egyptian pounds (51 U.S dollars) from 185 pounds (52.8 dollars)
late last year.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Sayed, head of the Suez Cement Company, said the
downturn was attributed to the efforts made by the government to
ensure a stable cement market.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to produce 26 million tons of cement this
year, up 2 million tons from 1999.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt Telecom on Monday decided cutting down
international call and Internet access fees to be consistent with
the global trend to reduce expenses of communication and internet
service.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Communication and Information Ahmad Nazif
said that fees on overseas phone calls to some Arab, European
countries and U.S. would be cut by 25 percent as of September 1.
</P>
<P>
Fees on access to the Internet via Egypt Telecom international
lines would be cut 30 percent, the second reduction since December
1999's 50 percent slash, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fees on access to the Internet via ordinary phone sets would
also be reduced by 50 percent starting October, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Due to increasing dominance of synthetic fabrics in
fashion, Turkey's traditional mohair exports fell from 599 tons in
1991 to 17 tons last year, reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The average price of export mohair dropped from 6 U.S. dollars
to 2.3 dollars in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Although mohair is a product of Angora goats, which existed
exclusively in Turkey until the 1850s, now the major producers are
the United States and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, world production is also falling in parallel with the
Turkish trend. Total mohair production fell from 26,200 tons in
1988 to only 7,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Gold 2001 International Ornament and Jewelry Fair,
which is scheduled to take place in Istanbul on January 14-20,
2001, will be initially introduced to an audience at the New York
International Jewelry Fair, which will take place prior to the
Istanbul fair.
</P>
<P>
The Gold 2001 fair will address representatives from the U.S.
jewelry sector, as well as those from North Africa, Gulf and
European countries.
</P>
<P>
It is aimed at introducing Turkey's jewelry sector to
international markets.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's State Ports and Airports Construction
Directorate (DLH) has announced that the final technical bids in
the tender to determine which consortium will be in charge of
constructing the proposed Bosphorus tube crossing will be submitted
on August 28.
</P>
<P>
The project envisages the construction of a railway link between
the European and Asian parts of Istanbul, which are separated by
the Sea of Marmara.
</P>
<P>
Three consortia, formed by companies from Turkey, Great Britain,
Japan, the Netherlands, the United States, Germany and France, have
so far submitted their bids. The total cost of the project is
projected at 1.6 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
