<HEADLINE> Asia to Discuss Prevention of Child Sex Tourism in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Tourism industry trainers from
10 Asian countries and regions will meet here next week to discuss
how to develop a regional network of training specialists on the
prevention of child sex tourism, the United Nations said in a
press release here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be the first regional and international
meeting to discuss how the tourism industry can participate in
preventing child sex tourism through training and development.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is organized by the Australia Campaign to End
Child Prostitution in partnership with the Human Resource
Development Section of the U.N. Economic and Social Commission for
Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Tourism training experts from governments and the private
sector, universities and tourism authorities in Australia,
Cambodia, China's Hong Kong, India, Laos, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam are expected to attend the two-
day meeting beginning on August 22.
</P>
<P>
Workshop participants will share experiences and discuss how to
develop programs to teach the industry about the prevention of
child sex tourism. They will be encouraged to share information on
teaching methodologies.
</P>
<P>
The outcomes will include the development of a regional network
for exchange of information and research and a strategy to
identify the needs of teachers and training providers at the local
and regional levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
