<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compulsory Primary Education to Be Introduced in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
accepted a recommendation that compulsory primary education should
be introduced up to Primary Six in the city state to meet future
challenges and bring up useful and responsible citizens, according
to a government release Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made by the Committee on Compulsory
Education, chaired by Senior Minister of State for Education Aline
Wong and set up in December 1999 to study the matter concerning
the proposed compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
In a report submitted in July 2000, the committee recommended
that compulsory education be introduced up to Primary Six in
national schools for Singapore citizens residing in Singapore,
subject to the exemption of certain categories of children,
including those with special needs and children attending
madrasahs (religious schools).
</P>
<P>
In his letter to confirm the government's acceptance of the
recommendations, Singapore Minister for Education and Second
Minister for National Defense Teo Chee Hean said these
recommendations "accommodate the aspirations and views of the
different communities in Singapore, reaffirm the important role
that our educational system plays in preparing our young to meet
future challenges and to grow up to be useful and responsible
citizens."
</P>
<P>
Under the recommendations, children attending the six madrasahs
which currently offer full-time religious education for children
and the San Yu Adventist School and those receiving home-schooling
should be exempted from compulsory education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
