<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death toll of Nigerian New Pipeline Fire Rises to 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the appalling
pipeline fire last Friday near Kalabar, a town of Nigeria' s
southeast Cross River State, has increased to 18.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian newspapers Tuesday quoted officials of the Nigeria
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) on the site as saying on
Monday that not less than 2,000 people including women and
children had thronged the area to scoop fuel on Friday night
before the incident.
</P>
<P>
Despite the tragedy however, they still littered the area on
Monday bailing fuel in jerricans which NNPC officials and
villagers were busy trying to flush out water from the dug
pipelines.
</P>
<P>
The few policemen deployed to the site could not effectively
push back the villagers still desperate to scoop fuel.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers quoted a woman involved in the scooping as
saying that one man who had warned the people to steer clear of
the area to no avail, struck a match in annoyance which resulted
in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Last month, two major pipeline fires took place in Warri,
capital of the country's southern Delta state, killing a combined
victim population of about 250.
</P>
<P>
Pipeline vandalism or "scooping", propelled by deeply rooted
poverty, is commonplace in the west African nation' s oil rich
Niger delta region, despite the huge risks involved. Nigerian
President Olusegun Obasanjo had accused black market vendors of
acting selfishly and encouraging the pipeline vandalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuation May Start Soon for Sunken Russian Sub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Ilya Klebanov said Tuesday that evacuation of the over 100 crew
from a sunken nuclear submarine would start shortly if the storm
in the Barents Sea calms down.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov, who leads a government commission probing the
incident, said a storm measuring five points continues to rage in
area of the accident but there are forecasts that it may slacken
in a few hours.
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose "Kursk" submarine went down to the bottom of
the Barents Sea on Sunday during an exercise of the Russian
Northern Fleet. Authorities said explosion or collision with a
foreign submarine could have caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there were two U.S. submarines nearby at
the time of the accident and they reported the sound of an
explosion.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov said if weather improves, the military will "most
resolutely begin the evacuation," the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said all the necessary means to do so have been concentrated
in the accident area, but there is no contact with the submarine
now due to the strong storm.
</P>
<P>
The rescuers and the submarine crew had maintained what was
described as "acoustic contact" before by sending sound signals
and deciphering the messages.
</P>
<P>
However, Klebanov said, the absence of communication does not
mean that reserve air regeneration systems are not functioning.
</P>
<P>
"If they are not, there is little oxygen left aboard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov admitted that "the situation is grave," but Moscow
does not want to request assistance from other countries in
dealing with the consequences of the accident or evacuating the
crew.
</P>
<P>
The United States, France and Britain had offered assistance,
Klebanov said.
</P>
<P>
"We have all the necessary technical capabilities that are no
worse than American," he said.
</P>
<P>
The "Kursk" was commissioned for the Russian Navy in 1995. It
has a displacement of 14,700-23,860 tons and can dive to depths of
up to 500 meters. The submarine is armed with torpedoes and "
Granite" cruise missiles. The vessel can operate autonomously for
up to 120 days and carries a 107-man crew, including 52 officers,
Interfax reported earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Sports Federations Refuse WADA Out-of-Competition Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Two of the 28 International
Olympic Summer Sports Federations (IFs) have refused to put its
athletes under the doping control program of the World Anti-Doping
Agency (WADA) before the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The two IFs are the International Gymnastics Federation (FIG)
and the International Modern Pentathlon Union (UIPM), according to
a WADA press release received here today.
</P>
<P>
Another IF, the International Volleyball Federation (FIVB), has
delayed negotiations so long as to risk the implementation of a
viable out-of-competition testing program in its sport before the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
So far, 25 of the 28 IFs have joined WADA's unannounced, out-of-
competition testing program, WADA said. 14 of these IFs have to
amend their doping control policies to allow for WADA testing.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with these agreements, WADA either has conducted
or soon will conduct 1,930 doping control tests, bringing the
agency 90 percent of the way toward reaching its goal of
conducting 2,150 tests before the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
The implementation of the other 10 percent of the tests relies on
the willingness of the three IFs that have yet to agree to submit
to the independent doping control program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
