<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior U.N. Official Says Visit to Iraq Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Benon Sevan, the executive
director of the United Nations oil-for-food program, said here
Tuesday that he is very happy with his current visit to Iraq and
has held "fruitful and cordial" talks with Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
Sevan was speaking at a press conference held at the Canal Hotel
in the eastern part of the Iraqi capital Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"I have very fruitful and cordial discussions with almost all
the ministers as well as the vice president of Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his two-week visit, he also visited the three northern
provinces of Dohuk, Erbil and Sulaimaniya.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the oil-for-food program, Sevan said that the
program is never meant to solve all the problems of the Iraqi
people. What he and his colleagues have been trying is to see "how
we can improve further the implementation of the program."
</P>
<P>
The program can never be a substitute for the normal economic
activity of Iraq, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his trip to Iraq, Sevan released a statement, declaring
that the U.N. humanitarian program is no substitute for the
resumption of normal economic activity in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "There is no doubt that the situation for many
in that country is significantly better than it was when the first
oil was exported under the program at the end of 1996."
</P>
<P>
Sevan is due to leave the country on Wednesday. He last visited
Iraq in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
The three-year-old oil-for-food program is an exemption to the
crippling U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq for its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The program allows Iraq to sell oil in return for food, medicine
and other humanitarian supplies to help offset the impacts of the
sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dispute Erupts Anew over Religious Grave on Blue Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIEURT, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli army engineering units
have crossed into south Lebanon and "annexed" a disputed grave
claimed by Muslims and Jews on the common border.
</P>
<P>
Several local papers called the Israeli action the gravest
border violation since the deployment of U.N. peacekeeping troops
in the Israeli-vacated zone of south Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese liaison office with the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) lodged a complaint with the UNIFIL command Monday,
demanding an urgent intervention to get the Israelis out of the
Sheikh Abbad grave site right on the U.N.-drawn Blue Line for
Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, As Safir newspaper reported that a U.N. officer said
Hezbollah guerrillas prevented a UNIFIL patrol from reaching the
disputed site to verify the encroachment.
</P>
<P>
"We went to the site but Hezbollah would not allow us near it,"
the unnamed U.N. officer said in an interview by An Nahar
newspaper. "We tried several times but they would not let us in."
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate comment from the Lebanese government or
Hezbollah's press center on the reported U.N. claim.
</P>
<P>
The disputed grave is located in the central sector of the
border on Tall Abbad, or Abbad's Hill. The Israelis claim that
Rabbi Ashi, a renowned Jewish theologian who lived 500 years ago,
is buried in that grave. Muslims contend the tomb belonged to an
Islamic cleric called Sheikh Abdullah Abbad, whose name was given
to the site for the last five centuries.
</P>
<P>
When the U.N. drew the Blue Line with which it measured the
authenticity of the Israeli withdrawal two months ago, two thirds
of the grave fell inside Lebanese territory and one third remained
in Israel. Lebanon and Israel had given the U.N. their agreement to
the split.
</P>
<P>
But local residents Monday saw Israeli troops with bulldozers
crossing into Abbad's Hill, removing the Lebanese flag from the
grave and raising their own after fencing off the entire site with
barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
Beirut has given UNIFIL the green light to deploy in the
liberated zone after it was ascertained that all previous border
violations by Israel had been terminated.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL was officially authorized by Lebanon to patrol the entire
length of the border with the exception of the Fatma Gate location,
where the Lebanese have been staging almost daily stone-throwing
attacks on Israeli troops and farmers on the opposite side of the
barb-wired fence.
</P>
<P>
Despite the UNIFIL deployment and the subsequent dispatch of a
task force made up of 500 Lebanese army troops and 500 policemen
into the vacated zone, Hezbollah remained in effective control of
large chunks of the liberated zone.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas have maintained their weapons and most of their
observation positions along the border, obviously with the consent
of the Lebanese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
