<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Maintains No-Ransom Policy in Hostage Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Tuesday that it will not deviate from its no-ransom policy in
dealing with hostages situations in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora made this clear as he
stressed that no ransom money for the hostages held by the Abu
Sayyaf in Jolo was aboard a Libyan plane that arrived in Manila
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan aircraft arrived here Monday night, ready to fly
some of the foreign hostages in Jolo to Tripoli, Libya, in case
they are released by their Abu Sayyaf kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that once they are released by their captors,
the hostages will be flown to Tripoli and handed over to their
respective governments.
</P>
<P>
"There is no such 25 million U.S. dollars payment. That I can
assure you," Zamora said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He also shared the optimism of chief government negotiator
Robert Aventajado that the hostages would be released within this
week.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said negotiators have so far convinced the Abu Sayyaf to
accept social development projects and livelihood opportunities in
exchange for the hostages' safe release.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful there will be some breakthroughs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is holding three French journalists abducted on
July 9 while the latter were covering the hostages crisis in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began on April 23 when Abu Sayyaf gunmen kidnapped
21 mostly foreign tourists and resort workers from the Malaysian
resort of Sipadan and brought them to Jolo.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf has released seven Sipadan hostages and three
reporters covering the hostages crisis after it was reportedly
paid up to 247.5 million pesos (6.2 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
