<HEADLINE> Russia Demands Immediate End to Air Raids on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday reiterated its
demand that the U.S. and British air forces immediately stop
bombing Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
Moscow "considers these actions illegal from the point of view
of international law," the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a
statement. "It (the bombing) must be stopped immediately."
</P>
<P>
The recent air raids caused casualties among the civilian
population, and homes, food storehouses and centers for
distributing humanitarian goods were destroyed, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The bombing of the Iraqi territory only increases tension in
the region."
</P>
<P>
"This is taking place at the exact moment the international
community is becoming convinced of the necessity to settle the
Iraqi problem through political and diplomatic means."
</P>
<P>
According to an Iraqi military spokesman, two Iraqis were
killed and 19 others injured in the U.S.-British air strikes
Saturday afternoon, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The air strikes followed Friday's air raids that killed one and
injured 20 others.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have been patrolling the two so-
called "no-fly zones" in the north and south of Iraq to protect
Kurds in the north and Shiite Muslims in the south from what they
called the persecution of the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
The zones have witnessed almost daily skirmishes since the
allies' air war on Iraq in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad does not recognize the zones, which were established
after the 1991 Gulf War but are not directly covered by a United
Nations resolution.
</P>
<P>
Iraq says the bombings have killed 300 innocent people, injured
1,000 others and inflicted huge property damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
