<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Sets aside Funds for Poverty Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has set
aside 20 billion shillings (about 267 million U.S. dollars) this
year for the poverty eradication program, Chairman Gilbert Oluoch
of the National Poverty Eradication Commission has announced.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Tuesday quoted Oluoch as
saying "the money has been released to benefit all less fortunate
people and will serve all of the country."
</P>
<P>
Oluoch made the remarks Monday when he was speaking at a
district development committee meeting in Mombasa, a port city in
southeastern Kenya, where stake holders discussed the review of
projects focusing on rural development.
</P>
<P>
He said attention will be given to medical, sanitation, water
and other basic needs that are part of the program, which will run
from year 2000 to 2015.
</P>
<P>
The funds for the poverty eradication program had already been
passed in this year's budget, Oluoch said, urging the commission,
nongovernmental organizations and private sector to strategize on
how the money will benefit the affected people.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the poverty eradication program in Mombasa can
only succeed if the district is free of the drug menace and called
upon all the stake holders to join hands in forming community-
based projects and rehabilitation centers to help fight drug
abuse in the city and Coast Province as a whole.  
</P>
</TEXT>
