<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Domestic Forex Deposits on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China's domestic foreign
exchange deposits increased 3.32 billion U.S. dollars in July, 2.
59 billion U.S. dollars more than the year-ago period, according
to statistics released here today by the People's Bank of China (
PBOC).
</P>
<P>
In the past seven months foreign exchange deposits saw an
accumulated increase of 13.8 billion U.S. dollars, 9.18 billion U.
S. dollars more than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of foreign exchange
deposits reached 117 billion U.S. dollars, up 25.9 percent from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In July corporate foreign exchange deposits increased 1.57
billion U.S. dollars, which is 2.06 billion U.S. dollars more than
the year-ago period. In the first seven months corporate foreign
exchange deposits increased a total of 3.63 billion U.S. dollars,
4.85 billion U.S. dollars more than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of corporate foreign
exchange deposits reached 43.5 billion U.S. dollars, up 16.8
percent from the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
In July, residents' foreign exchange deposits increased 1.67
billion U.S. dollars, 330 million U.S. dollars more than the same
month last year. In the first seven months such deposits increased
a total of 9.74 billion U.S. dollars, 2.64 billion U.S. dollars
more than the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of residents'
foreign exchange deposits reached 65.09 billion U.S. dollars, up
17.6 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of foreign exchange
loans was 67.5 billion U.S. dollars, 230 million U.S. dollars less
than the previous month in constant terms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
