<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Auto Giant Set to Meet State Pollution Control Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China First Automobile Group
Corp, one of the country's three major auto manufacturers, has
invested nearly 100 million yuan (12 million U.S. dollars) in air
and water pollution control projects over the past year.
</P>
<P>
 Song Xuezhi, director of the Security and Environmental
Protection Department of the company, said the investment, a sum
rarely seen before, aims to enable the auto giant to meet the
pollutant discharge standards set by the central government.
</P>
<P>
 The central government vowed four years ago to close down all
the polluting industrial firms that fail to meet industrial
pollution discharge standards by the end of this year to curb
growing industrial pollution following 18 years of high economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
 Located in Changchun, capital of northeastern China's Jilin
Province, the company has recently allocated 76 million yuan (9.1
million U.S. dollars) for centralized disposal of the sewage of a
disposal plant being built in western suburb of the city.
</P>
<P>
The company also earmarked 20 million yuan (2.4 million U.S.
dollars) last year for air pollution control projects.
</P>
<P>
Song said he is confident that his company will meet the State
standards by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The company, with 150,000 workers, reported a sale volume of
30 billion yuan (3.6 billion U.S. dollars) last year and the waste
water it produced each day topped 74,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Only 65% Spectacles Found Up to Standards: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Only 65.7 percent of the
spectacles were found up to standards by the State Bureau of
Technological Supervision in its latest nationwide sample survey.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of the survey conducted in the second
quarter of this year, only 94 of 143 pairs of spectacles selected
from 143 spectacles shops across the country passed the tests.
</P>
<P>
But 94 percent spectacles selected from large shops, or shops
whose annual sale volumes exceeding 5 million yuan (602,000 U.S.
dollars) were up to standard, while only 31.8 percent of those
selected from shops whose annual sale volumes less than 500,000
yuan (60,200 U.S. dollars) were up to standard.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said large spectacle shops are found to be equipped
with advanced equipment to ensure the quality of spectacles.
</P>
<P>
An outstanding problem with substandard spectacles produced by
small shops is that the shops were found to use spectacles with
less accurate diopters to substitute the prescribed ones which
they run short of, resulting in less satisfactory rectification of
eye sights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
