<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Reshuffles National Security Council, Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Chief Executive
General Pervez Musharraf Tuesday reconstituted the National
Security Council (NSC) which besides military chiefs will have
four federal ministers as its new members.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, President Rafiq Tarar also announced the
nomination of four members to the federal cabinet.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf, who is also army chief, will be NSC chairman
and naval and air force chiefs will continue to serve on the top
executive organ, it was officially announced here.
</P>
<P>
The minister of commerce, minister of finance, minister for
foreign affairs and minister for interior will also be members of
the reconstituted NSC.
</P>
<P>
The NSC now has seven members instead of eight before.
</P>
<P>
Among the five former NSC members, Attiya Inayatullah has been
appointed as minister for women development, social welfare and
special education and Mehmood Ghazi has become minister for
religious affairs.
</P>
<P>
Sharif ud Din Pirzada has become honorary advisor to the chief
executive on foreign affairs, law, justice and human rights and
Shafi Niaz advisor to the chief executive on food, agriculture and
livestock while Imtiaz Ahmad Sahibzada has been appointed as
chairman of the Federal Land Commission.
</P>
<P>
The other two new cabinet members are Jave Asharaf as minister
for communications and Col. (Retired) Trassler as minister for
sports, minority affairs and youth in place of Derrick Cyprian who
has resigned on personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
President Tarar has also appointed Iftikhar Hussain Shah as
governor of Northwest Frontier Province in place of Muhammad
Sahfiq who resigned on personal reasons on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
