<HEADLINE> Share Prices Up in Tokyo for Third Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in
Tokyo for the third straight trading day Tuesday, led mainly by
export-oriented high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 144.38 points, or 0.89
percent, from Monday's close to end at 16,298.29.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 6.88 points, or 0.46 percent, to 1,
500.31.
</P>
<P>
Trading, however, remained thinning amid the summer holiday
season, with turnover on the major section totaling 475.45 million
shares, slightly up from Monday's 450.10 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Furukawa Electric was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Semiconductor-related issues were boosted by gains of their U.S.
counterparts Monday, while the yen's weakness against the U.S.
dollar also led exporters higher, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Electric wire and cable makers were up on expectations for
progress in the information technology sector.
</P>
<P>
Gainers included the consumer finance, brokerage and air
transportation sectors, while electric power and gas firms, oil
distributors, the paper, rubber and real estate sectors faced
selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 735 to 482, with 161 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
