<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Seven Chinese cities, namely
Beijing, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Zhengzhou, Changsha, Lanzhou and
Xining, reported slight air pollution today, with the highest
pollution reading at 127 in Taiyuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two or fairly good air
quality was recorded in the following 28 cities: Tianjin, Hohhot,
Shenyang, Changchun, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Fuzhou, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Wuhan,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Chongqing, Chengdu,
Guiyang, Kunming, Xi'an, Yinchuan and Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major
pollutants in most of the cities, except Nantong, Chongqing,
Guiyang and Kunming, where sulfur dioxide was the major air
pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Seven cities -- Dalian, Harbin, Xiamen, Zhuhai, Nanning, Haikou
and Lhasa -- reported excellent air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level one or excellent (pollution readings: not
exceeding 50), level two or fairly good (pollution readings: 51 to
100), level three or slightly polluted (pollution readings: 101 to
200), level four or poor (pollution readings: 201 to 300), and
level five or hazardous (pollution readings: over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four
municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing,
provincial capitals and major cities in the economically developed
coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Studying Anti-Hacking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have begun to
research on an "anti-hacking system" to prevent the rampage of
hackers on the Internet, according to the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The study is being conducted by a group of experts led by Xu
Rongsheng, a research fellow with the High-Energy Physics
Institute under the CAS.
</P>
<P>
The scientists are working on basic theories, high technology
and effective ways to monitor and respond to the activities of
hackers, so as to ensure the safety of information networks.
</P>
<P>
China needs professionals in combating hackers, said Xu, who
hopes the study could attract a number of talented young people
with necessary expertise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
