<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- If Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
ignores advice he is hearing in various capitals and unilaterally
declares a state on September 13, the European Union is likely not
to recognize the state, a Western diplomat said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite declarations by various Palestinian officials that no
decision will be made until the Palestinian Liberation
Organization's Central Council, the top policy-making body, meets
on the matter during the first week of September, the diplomat said
the EU's assessment is that Arafat will not declare a state then,
but will make do with some other symbolic act of sovereignty or
statehood, such as issuing formal Palestinian passports.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Finance Minister Avraham Shochat signed an order on
Monday reducing the purchase tax on 630 consumer goods as well as
on manufacturing costs, totalling 1.3 billion shekels (about 325
million U.S. dollars) per year. The 65 percent purchase tax on
vehicles has not been reduced.
</P>
<P>
Shochat said that he hoped that dealers, wholesalers and
retailers would pass on the tax benefits to consumers.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tax reduction was a progressive move that would
minimize inequality in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
