<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Lower Perinatal Mortality Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Recent perinatal mortality
rates in New Zealand are the lowest ever recorded, according to
the latest information from the New Zealand Health Information
Service.
</P>
<P>
The service Tuesday released fetal and infant deaths numbers in
1997 which show that in that year for every 1,000 births there
were 10.2 perinatal deaths(stillbirths after 20 weeks of pregnancy
and deaths of babies in the first week of life). Provisional data
for 1998 and 1999 show rates of 8.1 and 9 per 1,000 total births,
the lowest ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
John Marwick, a senior advisor with the New Zealand Ministry of
Health, said in a ministry's press release that figures vary a
little from year to year, "but the general trend has been
improving.The 1998 figure looks to be one of the lowest rates in
the world ahead of Australia, the UK, Canada and the U.S."
</P>
<P>
He also said the number of women dying during pregnancy or
after delivery was very low. "Maternal mortality data takes longer
to determine but trends also seem to be improving with the number
of maternal deaths dropping from four in 1996 to only two deaths
registered in 1997." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
