<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Envoy to Return to Fiji, But Sanctions Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's high
commissioner is returning to Fiji but the government says it has
no plans to relax sanctions at the moment, according to The
Dominion.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper Tuesday quoted New Zealand
Foreign Minister Phil Goff as saying High Commissioner Tia Barrett,
who was withdrawn for consultations in mid-July, will return to
Suva at the end of the week together with the Australian high
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Goff said the commissioner's return is in "recognition of the
step forward Fiji has taken by charging coup leader George Speight
and 13 of his collaborators with treason."
</P>
<P>
"We welcome that as an advance as we welcome the restoration of
law and order...in Fiji," he said.
</P>
<P>
A few days ago, New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark said
charging Speight and his supporters with treason is "a necessary
step on the long road back to restoring Fiji's international
reputation."
</P>
<P>
She said the move was "encouraging."
</P>
<P>
New Zealand has also been imposing aid, development, diplomatic,
military and sporting sanctions against Fiji since Speight plunged
the country into crisis when he toppled the Fiji government headed
by Mahendra Chaudhry on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government will not reconsider its sanctions
till it sees some firm commitment to a return to democracy, Goff
was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He held that things in Fiji have not returned to normal yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
