<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Rates Sydney Olympic Organisers "Bronze" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace Tuesday given Sydney
Olympic organisers six out of ten for their environmental
practices - one point less than last year.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace Olympics campaigner Blair Palese said while there
had been outstanding environmental successes, the failures were
disappointing and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Greenpeace gave the Games a "bronze" for its
environmental performance.
</P>
<P>
Palese said key failures included the fact there was no clean-
up plan for the toxic waste in Homebush Bay and Rhodes Peninsula
and the use of non-environmentally friendly air-conditioning and
refrigeration in venues.
</P>
<P>
Palese said the confusion over which body will manage the toxic
waste at the site after the Games and the failure to keep
environmental records were also failures.
</P>
<P>
Streets ice-creams had also failed to comply with the waste
strategy by using plastic wrappers.
</P>
<P>
Palese said the bronze medal, or C grade, performance, meant
that organisers had just crossed the line in making the Sydney
Olympics the "Green Games."
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace was part of Sydney's Olympic bid, the first to
include environmental guidelines, and has been assessing
preparations ever since.
</P>
<P>
"Solutions to environmental problems do exist," Palese said.
</P>
<P>
"The Sydney Olympics could have been a world class showcase for
these solutions, instead they just managed to scrape in under the
title, Green Games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympics Weather to be Drier than Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The weather in Sydney will be "
drier than average" during the Olympic Games, a weather forecaster
predicted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sydney's Meteorology Bureau meteorologist Robert Fawcett said
September was typically the driest month of the year.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage we have nothing to suggest September will be
wetter or drier but looking historically September is drier than
average over the year," Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
"If we include October and November in the equation, within our
usual three-monthly forecasts, the chance of rainfall increases to
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"However, this (forecast) is only for statistical purposes," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said September usually receives around 70 mm of rain, as
compared to March and June, which receives 134 mm and 132mm
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney bid committee used these figures as a selling point
in its successful bid for the 2000 Olympic Games in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
