<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Doubles Tea Imports From Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an interview with local media on Monday, Minister of
Internal and International Commerce and Food Kingsley T.
Wickremeratne said that the two countries signed an agreement on
the tea imports at the Sri Lanka-Iran Joint Commission meeting
held at Iranian capital Teheran earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Iran imported 9,000 tons of Sri Lankan tea. The
quantity of tea to be imported this year will well exceed 20,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement Sri Lanka will give Iran a three month
credit line for tea exports and will in return receive a six-month
credit line for petroleum imports from Iran, the supplier of 60
percent of Sri Lanka's crude oil requirements.
</P>
<P>
There will also be an increase in rubber exports to Iran for
its tire industry and also spices, the Minister added.
</P>
<P>
He said that also under consideration is the establishment of a
tea blending factory in Kish Island, Iran. The factory, a joint
venture, will re-export Sri Lankan tea under the Ceylon tea label
to Russian markets.
</P>
<P>
Wikremeratne said that an Iranian team of businessmen will
visit Colombo shortly to establish joint venture industries to
manufacture carpets, chandeliers, melamine and furniture to meet
the demand in the South Asian markets using Colombo as the base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee Delivers Independence Day Address Amid Tight Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"To achieve this ambitious target we have to make many
important reforms in our economy. At the same time, we need to
implement necessary reforms in our administration, our judiciary,
in education and in other areas," said Vajpayee in a 30-minute
address to the nation marking India's 54th Independence Day here
Tuesday morning. India's per capital gross national product was
440 U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Giving his address in Hindi from the rampart of the historic
site of Red Fort, where former Indian Prime Minister Jawahar Lal
Nehru announced India's independence on August 15, 1947, Vajpayee
said his government would take "many big and important steps" this
year to accelerate economic and social development and bring its
benefits to the people, promising the interest of workers would be
fully taken into account in the economic reform process.
</P>
<P>
On India's relations with Pakistan, Vajpayee once again accused
Islamabad of sabotaging recent peace talks between the Indian
government and Hizbul Mujahideen, a major militant outfit in
Kashmir, and ruled out any dialogue with Pakistan till it stops "
cross-border terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"Nobody should underestimate India's willingness and ability to
deal firmly with violence, terrorism, extremism and separatism,"
he asserted.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the prime minister also declared his government
's resolve to intensify its campaign against corruption among high-
ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
"Our country cannot make expected progress in development
without probity in administration and in public life," he noted. "
We shall intensify our campaign against corruption in high place."
</P>
<P>
Describing the rapidly spreading HIV/AIDS as a grave challenge
to the nation, Vajpayee said all sections of society should fully
participate in creating awareness about the disease.
</P>
<P>
"They should also make necessary changes in their behavior so
that this disease can be controlled," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also made a series of promises on behalf of
his government to the Indian people, including a road project to
connect all villages with a population of more than 1,000 in the
next three years, clean drinking water for every village and
hamlet in next four years, education upto class eight for every
Indian child and free education for women by 2010, as well as
access to computers and Internet for every school and every
village in "as less time as possible."
</P>
<P>
Stating that India needs more social justice in the new century,
Vajpayee said: "Our independence is incomplete without social
justice."
</P>
<P>
"We need that kind of social justice that also promotes social
harmony," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving at the Red Fort, Vajpayee paid floral tributes
at the mausoleum of India's founding father Mahatma Gandhi at
Rajghat. He also hoisted a tri-color national flag before giving
his address.
</P>
<P>
However, India's first Independence Day of the new millennium
was celebrated amidst unprecedented security in the wake of
threats from militant groups, especially those from Kashmir, to
intensify their attacks.
</P>
<P>
In the Indian capital, over 55,000 local police and
paramilitary personnel formed a tight security blanket which, in
the words of the quasi-official Press Trust of India, almost
turned the city into an "impregnable fortress."
</P>
<P>
While the prime minister was speaking from behind a bullet-
proof glass shield, Indian Air Force helicopters maintained vigil
from the skies and air corridors remained closed till the end of
the address. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
