<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- Visiting Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez Monday
called on oil-producing countries to resist demands to cut oil
prices in the international market, saying the current prices were
fair and any attempt to change them would be passing a death
sentence on their countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference in the Nigerian capital
Abuja on Monday with his Nigerian counterpart Olusegun Obasanjo,
Chavez said some powerful countries were using blackmail to force
down the price of the crude oil in spite of the fact that buyers
made as much as 100 U.S. dollars from each barrel of the commodity
bought at less than 30 dollars. (Nigeria-Venezuela-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- Angola is preparing to sign a free-trade protocol
that rules trade and economic exchanges among the member countries
of the Southern African Development Community(SADC), said an
official from the Angolan Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Rui Mangueira, director of the Regional Economic Integration of
the Foreign Ministry, was quoted here on Monday by the official
news agency Angop as saying that "it's fundamental for Angola to
integrate itself, effectively, with the economies of other SADC
member countries, through the entrance into the free-trade zone of
the community." (Angola-SADC-Free Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- U.S. Businesses have significantly changed their
Web-spending patterns in the past year,an American market research
firm reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gone are the days of Web spending to build an Internet presence,
according to International Data Corporation (IDC), and in their
place is spending to integrate the Internet into internal and
external business process. In other words, purchases of Web-
related technology are now a business imperative, IDC's report
said.
</P>
<P>
"Today, corporate Internet spending is an investment that
directly impacts the strategic direction of organizations," said
the report. "The strategic impact remains, but it has shifted from
reducing costs to the transformation of business models."(U.S.-
Businesses-Web-Spending Patterns)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO -- The North America Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA)
intensified exchange between Mexico and the United States, and
also raised controversies, said Mexico's Trade Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Since NAFTA came into effect, the United States has filed 17
claims against Mexican exports, said the secretariat in a report
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, U.S. products represent a third of
investigations into unfair trade in Mexico, it added.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is the second most important trade partner of the United
States after Canada. Trade between Mexico and the United States
went from 81 billion dollars in 1993, a year before NAFTA came
into effect, to some 200 billion dollars in 1999. (Mexico-US-
Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuador's yearly inflation reached 102.3 percent in
July, the weekly economic journal "Lideres" reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Compared to other nations in the region, the situation is "
worrying," says an article in the journal.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela has a 17.9 percent yearly inflation, Mexico 10.5
percent, Haiti 10 percent, Brazil 8.9 percent, Colombia 8.5
percent, Paraguay 6.4 percent, Peru 3.9 percent, Uruguay 3.9
percent, Bolivia 3.6 percent and El Salvador 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
With this high inflation rate, international investors will
hardly pay attention to the country unless they find another kind
of attraction Ecuador could offer, the article said. (Ecuador-
Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Poland's State Treasury Minister Emil Wasacz was
dismissed on Monday and replaced by Andrezej Chronowski, deputy
speaker of the Polish Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Chronowski, 39, is also from the Solidarity Election Action
Union and has been the deputy speaker of the parliament since
November 1997
</P>
<P>
This is the second reshuffle of the government led by the
Solidarity Union in less than three months. The Freedom Union, the
second largest party in Poland's ruling coalition, withdrew from
the cabinet in early June.
</P>
<P>
Wasacz was forced to resign from within and without his party
after several major mistakes were made in the ministry, since he
assumed the office in October 1997. (Poland-Treasury Minister
Replacement) 
</P>
