<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Launches 1st Optical Fiber Telecom Transmission Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched its first
optical fiber inter- province telecommunication transmission ring
at a cost of 1,500 million rupees (around 19.1 million U.S.
dollars), the Island newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, an optical fiber cable was laid connecting
the telephone exchanges of 15 major cities and urban centers
encompassing four provinces.
</P>
<P>
The ring circles the capital city of Colombo, Gampaha, Negombo,
Chilaw, Kurunegala, Kegalle, Matale, Kandy, Nuwara Eliya, Hatton,
Nawalapitiya, Avissawela, Ratnapura, Kalutara, Mt Lavinia with a
total route length of about 700 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The system is equipped with a sophisticated Network Management
Center in Colombo which can monitor the entire network and enables
it to give necessary instructions for the delivery of service in
each part of its system.
</P>
<P>
The system will increase by many folds Sri Lanka Telecom's
capacity and strengthen its backbone transmission network with a
high degree of reliability due to its self-feeding ability.
</P>
<P>
As a light signal carries the message through the cable, there
can be no interference during its travel and it will be immune to
noise. It also enhances the quality and clarity of its voice
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
