<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 112 Dams Built in Myanmar in 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 15 (Xinhua) - Altogether 112 dams have been
built in Myanmar since late 1988 when the present government took
office, irrigating 607,500 hectares of farmland, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The dams include 25 in Bago, 19 in Magway and 29 in Mandalay
divisions.
</P>
<P>
Dams were built in the Bago division to prevent flood and water
shortage which usually occur in the western part of the division,
the main sugarcane growing region of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Magway and the Mandalay divisions, which lie in
the central arid zone, are main producers of beans and pulses,
edible oil crops and cotton.
</P>
<P>
The Bago and Magway divisions are also among Myanmar's six
divisions and states where vacant, virgin and fallow lands are
being reclaimed by private entrepreneurs to promote the country's
agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's agriculture accounts for 37 percent of the country's
gross domestic product and 25 percent of its export value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
