<HEADLINE> Krayzelburg, Kowal Impressive in U.S. Olympic Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- World record-holder Lenny
Krayzelburg and world champion Kristy Kowal both won their
specialities as expected at the U.S. Olympic swimming trials in
Indianapolis Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Krayzelburg, 24, remained unchallenged in the backstroke events
by anchoring his second straight victory of 1:57.31 in the men's
200m backstroke, following his first triumph in the 100m
backstroke in 53.84 seconds days ago.
</P>
<P>
Aaron Peirsol, who topped the semifinals Sunday evening,
finished second in 1:57.98 for his first ticket towards the Sydney
Olympic Games as only the top two qualify from each event.
</P>
<P>
Krayzelburg, who holds the world records in the 50m, 100m and
200m backstrokes, becomes a sure bet for the gold medals in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Kristy Kowal also made the Olympics by setting a new American
record in the women's 200m breaststroke in 2:24.75, followed by
Amanda Beard who also secured her first Olympic ticket in 2:26.79.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the 21-year-old world champion finished a
disappointing third in the 100m breaststroke, missing the Olympic
team by only 0.01 seconds. Four years ago, she also missed the
Atlanta Games by the slimmest of margins. 
</P>
