<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rejects U.S. Criticism Over Wahid's Iraq Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
rejected U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's warning that
President Abdurrahman Wahid should cancel a planned visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cannot pose "a threat and intimidation" against a
sovereign country's leader who plans to visit another country,
Indonesian Foreign Affairs Ministry spokesman Sulaiman Abdulmanan
told the Indonesian Observer on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"The planned trip does not contravene the principles of foreign
politics," Sulaiman said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Wahid called for the lifting of international
sanctions against Iraq and said he would visit that country at the
end of this summer.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Saturday, Albright said that such a
trip would be "inappropriate and ill-advised." She urged Wahid to
heed Washington's advice.
</P>
<P>
"It's not up to me to tell Wahid what to do, I think, however,
it does not enhance the stature of any country to go there,"
Albright said. 
</P>
