<HEADLINE> Romanian FM Swims in Danube Calling for Clearing NATO-bomb Debris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Foreign Minister
Petre Roman swam in the Danube on Monday, urging clearing debris
from the river left over from last year's NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
At Calarasi, 130 kilometers southeast of Bucharest, Roman
joined 46-year-old Slovenian swimmer Martin Strel, a swimming
champion of former Yugoslavia, who started a marathon protest swim
in the Danube on June 20.
</P>
<P>
The Danube, Europe's second longest waterway after the Volga,
has been blocked by bridge debris resulted from NATO bombing
against Yugoslavia, affecting countries downstream, notably
Romania and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Strel began his Danube swim at Donaueschingen, Germany, 40 to
60 kilometers a day, and is scheduled to finish it on August 24 at
Tulcea, where the Danube flows into the Black Sea on the Romanian
coast. 
</P>
