<HEADLINE> Paraguay Electoral Board to Re-count Votes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Paraguay's Electoral Board
ordered Monday to re-count votes in Sunday's vice presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
The position of vice president remained vacant ever since March
23, 1999, when the former Vice President Maria Argana was murdered.
It was the first time in Paraguay's history that elections only
for a vice president were held.
</P>
<P>
Among 2 million legitimate voters, only 51.08 percent turned
out, recording a marked non-participation.
</P>
<P>
The liberal opposition candidate, Julio Cesar Franco got,
according to the preliminary results announced by the Electoral
Board on Sunday night, won 47.7 percent of the votes, while the
ruling party candidate, Felix Argana, got 46.93 percent, after 90
percent of the votes were counted.
</P>
<P>
If Franco is confirmed as the winner, this will be the first
victory of the Liberal Radical Authentic Party (PLRA) in 53 years,
during which the Colorado Party has been in power.
</P>
<P>
A Supreme Court judge said that the winner of the elections
will have the possibility to claim the presidency currently held
by Luis Gonzalez Macchi, who came to power after former President
Raul Cubas resigned following the murder.
</P>
<P>
Macchi's term expires on August 15, 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
