<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers of South Pacific Nations Meet in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The 6th foreign ministerial
meeting of the members of the Southern Pacific Permanent
Commission (SPPC) opened here Monday to discuss marine species
preservation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers are Soledad Alvear from Chile, Guillermo
Fernandez from Colombia, Heinz Moeller from Ecuador, and Fernando
de Trazegnies from Peru, besides Permanent Secretary of the
commission Fabian Valdiviesco.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on preserving South Pacific's marine species was
scheduled to be signed at during meeting.
</P>
<P>
Among the most pressing issues are the banning on port access
to vessels fishing in high seas without abiding to the
conservation measures decided by the parties to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Once agreement, known as the Galapagos Accord, comes into
effect, the member countries will determine protection measures
for trans-zone and highly migrating species such as albacore and
yellow jack.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, the four ministers and the SPPC permanent
secretary met in the La Moneda Palace with Chile's President
Ricardo Lagos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
