<HEADLINE> Mexico: Free Trade Raises Controversies With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The North America Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA) intensified exchange between Mexico and the
United States, and also raised controversies, said Mexico's Trade
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Since NAFTA came into effect, the United States has filed 17
claims against Mexican exports, said the secretariat in a report
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, U.S. products represent a third of
investigations into unfair trade in Mexico, it added.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is the second most important trade partner of the United
States after Canada. Trade between Mexico and the United States
went from 81 billion dollars in 1993, a year before NAFTA came
into effect, to some 200 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Mexican products facing U.S. sanctions include oil, livestock,
rubber, wire, lamb, tomato, millet brooms, TV sets, steel pipes
and plates.
</P>
<P>
"As trade relations expands, it is natural that controversies
take place. The treaty has dispositions to solve them," the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Inflation Reaches 102.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's yearly inflation reached
102.3 percent in July, the weekly economic journal "Lideres"
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Compared to other nations in the region, the situation is "
worrying," says an article in the journal.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela has a 17.9 percent yearly inflation, Mexico 10.5
percent, Haiti 10 percent, Brazil 8.9 percent, Colombia 8.5
percent, Paraguay 6.4 percent, Peru 3.9 percent, Uruguay 3.9
percent, Bolivia 3.6 percent and El Salvador 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
With this high inflation rate, international investors will
hardly pay attention to the country unless they find another kind
of attraction Ecuador could offer, the article said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
