<HEADLINE> American Countries Start Joint Military Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Military personnel from 18
American countries started Monday in Honduras the "Operation for
Peace-North 2000" practice co-sponsored by the United Nations and
the U.S. Southern Army Command.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 naval and air forces officers from Central America
countries, Caribbean countries and the United States, besides
representatives from government and non-government organizations,
were involved in the event, which will finish on August 25, U.S.
and Honduran military officials said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Honduran army Colonel Jorge Andino said that the event, which
has been organized a year in advance, had no direct relationship
whatsoever with current events or circumstances in the region.
</P>
<P>
The goals were to share experiences in peacekeeping operations,
to examine current challenges, to increase peacekeeping capability
and to promote regional and multinational cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The joint practice would serve to enhance coordination between
armed forces and the United Nations, government and non-government
agencies in peacekeeping and humanitarian operation.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Julius Clark, vice chief of operations of the U.S. Army,
said his country had invested 2.3 million dollars in the operation.
</P>
<P>
The Commander of the U.S. Military Group in Honduras, Colonel
Mario Garza, said that since 1988 there had been 16 operations of
the kind.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 18 non-government organizations in the
region also participated in the "Operation for Peace-North 2000."
</P>
<P>
The participating countries are Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas,
Barbados, Belize, Dominica, Dominican Republic, El Salvador,
United States, Granada, Guatemala, Guayana, Honduras, Nicaragua,
Santa Lucia, St. Kitts &AMP; Nevis, San Vicente, Surinam and Trinidad
and Tobago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
