<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Only Three Federations yet to Join out-of-competition Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Anti-Doping Agency (
WADA) said on Monday that only three international summer sports
federations have yet to join the program for unannounced out-of-
competition doping tests ahead of the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The International Gymnastics Federation and the International
Modern Pentathlon Union have so far refused to submit to the WADA
program while the International Volleyball Federation has delayed
the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
WADA, set up last year to coordinate a worldwide testing
campaign for banned performance-enhancing drugs, said it so far
has conducted 680 tests and plans to carry out another 1,250
before the Olympics open on September 15.
</P>
<P>
That will bring it to 90 percent of the goal of 2,150 before
the start of the games.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of the other 10 percent of the tests relies
on the willingness of the three federations that have yet to agree
to submit to the independent doping control program," WADA said.
</P>
</TEXT>
