<HEADLINE> Xinhua Middle East News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BIEURT -- Israeli army engineering units have crossed into south
Lebanon and "annexed" a disputed grave claimed by Muslims and Jews
on the common border.
</P>
<P>
Several local papers called the Israeli action the gravest
border violation since the deployment of U.N. peacekeeping troops
in the Israeli-vacated zone of south Lebanon last week.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese liaison office with the U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) lodged a complaint with the UNIFIL command Monday,
demanding an urgent intervention to get the Israelis out of the
Sheikh Abbad grave site right on the U.N.-drawn Blue Line for
Israeli withdrawal. (Lebanon-UN-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said on Tuesday
that Israel will push ahead its peace-making efforts with the
Palestinians, but will not rush for peace at any price.
</P>
<P>
Touring the southern town of Eshkolot, Barak said even if Israel
cannot find a sincere peace partner in the peace process, it still
can win international support for its efforts, Israel Radio
reported.(Israel-Peace-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Responsible for the
Middle East, Edward Walker, described here on Tuesday the
differences between the sides in the Middle East peace process as "
small."
</P>
<P>
The American envoy added in an upbeat tone that a compromise can
be reached between the Palestinians and Israel soon, reported the
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"Our optimism is that because the differences are somewhat
small, we will be able to reach an agreement in the not too distant
future," he said. (U.S.-Mideast Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Knesset, or Parliament, decided Tuesday
afternoon to call another special meeting during the summer recess
to discuss the possible renewal of the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's Knesset session, which itself was a special session in
the summer recess beginning on August 2, made the decision after 39
legislators voted for the motion, while only one Knesset member
voted against it. (Israel-Parliament-Special Session)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq said that the U.S. and British warplanes bombed
its northern part on Tuesday, but reported no damage or casualties.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
an Iraqi military spokesman said that at 11:20 local time (0720
GMT), seven formations of the U.S. and British planes carried out
14 armed sorties over the three northern provinces of Dohuk,
Neiveva and Erbil. (Iraq-US-Bombing) 
</P>
