<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Honors Agents in Elian Raid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government on
Tuesday honored 114 federal agents for their predawn raid in April
that resulted in taking away Cuban boy Elian Gonzalez from his
Miami relatives who tried to separate the boy from his reunion
with his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held in Glynco, Georgia, where Immigration and
Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner praised the
agents for their successful "operation Reunion."
</P>
<P>
"You not only did the right thing, you did it extraordinarily
well," Meissner said. "The objective of the operation was to
remove Elian safely from the home of his great uncle and reunite
him with his father. That was accomplished."
</P>
<P>
Elian, a six-year-old boy, was kept by his great-uncle Lazaro
Gonzalez and other relatives in Miami after his rescue from the
sea in Florida last November. They refused to hand over the boy
for the reunion with his father and a ship wreck incident soon
became highly politicized.
</P>
<P>
On April 22 shortly after 5 a.m., armed U.S. agents stormed
Lazaro Gonzalez' home and snatched the boy from a closet and
hustled him into a waiting van. 
</P>
