<HEADLINE> Two U.N. Agencies Contribute to Offset Drought Effects in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) announced on Tuesday that it would
immediately provide 75,000 U.S. dollars to combat the effects of a
devastating drought in Iran.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF said as the greatest need was for drinking water, it
would support the provision of safe drinking water to affected
population primarily in the five hardest hit provinces.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF's funds will be made available to local authorities
through the Minister of Interior for the purchase of stationary
water tankers, bladders, jerricans, chemicals and other water
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) had earlier
contributed 60,000 dollars to the relief effort in the hardest-hit
provinces.
</P>
<P>
A multi-disciplinary United Nations assessment mission recently
toured the worst affected provinces. The mission's initial
findings revealed that more than 50 percent of Iran's population
are affected by the drought to varying degrees. Over 800,000
animals have already died because of lack of water, malnutrition
and disease, and more losses are expected.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations appealed to the international community to
generously assist in alleviating the suffering caused by the
drought upon the lives of many Iranians, particularly vulnerable
groups such as children, women and nomadic livestock raisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
