<HEADLINE> White Farmers' Offer on Land Issue Unconstitutional: Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
respects the offer of 200 farms per year for resettlement by the
Commercial Farmers Union (CFU), but the offer is unconstitutional,
a senior government official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information and Publicity Jonathan Moyo
said in a statement that the offer fell out of the policy
framework governing land reform program.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution, the government will compulsorily
acquire more than five million hectares of land from white farmers
for resettlement.
</P>
<P>
The CFU had said it was prepared to avail 200 farms each year
to the government to start the land redistribution process.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said, "We hope this offer represents a new thinking in the
CFU and that it indicates a fresh appreciation of the urgency of
the land reform program."
</P>
<P>
"Accordingly, we hope the CFU is sincere in its offer and that
it will not use the offer as a public relations exercise designed
to hold or reverse the land reform program," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moyo said the government was willing to have dialog with those
committed to solving the land problem and welcomed the withdrawal
of litigation by the CFU.
</P>
<P>
The CFU had previously taken court action against President
Robert Mugabe, Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri and war
veterans leader Chejerai Hunzvi for failing to remove war veterans
from white-owned commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister said the government would soon launch a
publicity program to ensure that the public fully understand the
land issue.
</P>
<P>
He said the program would describe the constitutional,
technical and administrative details that govern the land reform
program in all the country's major languages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
