<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Boost Agriculture Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Erastus Mwencha, secretary-
general of Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA),
Wednesday urged member states of the regional group to boost
agriculture for their economic development.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop on agricultural development held here on
Wednesday, Mwench said agriculture is expected to be the biggest
beneficiary of the COMESA Free Trade Area (FTA).
</P>
<P>
He said the FTA will lead to the crumbling of national
boundaries, enabling agricultural producers to sell their products
in any COMESA member state where prices are good and demand is
buoyant.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said although FTA eliminates import duties and
completely removes non-tariff barriers and other obstacles,
restrictions and bottlenecks in intra-COMESA trade, this is
necessary but not sufficient to dynamise the economies of the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Agriculture is the main stay of our economies and the backbone
for our survival," he said, adding that Africa has to invest and
develop agriculture and there is no alternative in its development
strategy.
</P>
<P>
In eastern and southern Africa region, between 60 and 85
percent of people derive their income, employment and sustenance
from agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
