<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Vows to Continue Dis-engagement Plan Over Congo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has vowed
to continue with its dis-engagement plan to facilitate the
deployment of U. N. peacekeeping force to end the conflicts in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Rwanda News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda will tirelessly support any move aimed at peacefully
resolving the Congo conflict, especially the Lusaka summit and
facilitating the deployment of the U.N. troops," the news agency
quoted Rwandan President Paul Kagame as saying Tuesday evening
upon his arrival at Kanombe International Airport in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Kagame had just returned from the Lusaka summit, which began on
Monday and ended Tuesday morning in an effort to bring an end to
the DRC conflict.
</P>
<P>
Although DRC President Laurent Kabila resisted everything
discussed and also rejected former Botswana president Ketumile
Masire as facilitator of the inter-Congolese dialogue and to allow
U.N. peacekeepers unlimited access throughout the DRC, "the Lusaka
results were good," Kagame said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "we shall continue to support the Lusaka peace
accord," which was signed by all belligerents last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Kagame, Kabila's intentions, manifested by buying
more weapons and rejection of the new peace mediator, is a clear
indication that he does not back the peaceful resolution of the
DRC conflict.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, press reports quoted Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, Kabila's main ally, as saying that "President Kabila had
refused to listen or discuss the matter. He says he does not want
Ketumile Masire."
</P>
<P>
According to a final communique issued after the Lusaka summit,
leaders of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) urged
Kabila to reconsider his position and threatened sanctions if he
remained defiant.
</P>
<P>
All SADC countries are in support of Masire as the facilitator
with the exception of the DRC, the communique said, re-affirming
its support for the Lusaka ceasefire agreement as the only
accepted and viable basis for resolving the conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The summit, among other things, addressed such issues as cease-
fire violations, deployment of U.N. peacekeepers, resources of the
Joint Military Commission and DRC inter-political negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
