<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Welcomes Withdrawal of Litigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Vice President Joseph
Msika Wednesday expressed welcome to the move by the Commercial
Farmers Union (CFU) to withdraw its litigation against the
government over land raids by war veterans.
</P>
<P>
"I am going to reply and say we appreciate that they want to
work with us. This will make my task easier as it is a step in the
right direction," Msika said.
</P>
<P>
"If farmers continue to play games we will lose control of the
people," he said. "We want to establish a system that will not
bring chaos but sustain stability."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the fast-track land resettlement program, Msika
said the landless people would have been resettled before the
rainy season.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 3,000 farms have already been identified for
resettlement, he said.
</P>
<P>
CFU withdrew its litigation against the government last week.
President Robert Mugabe, Police Commissioner Augustine Chihuri and
war veterans leader Chenjerai Hunzvi were supposed to respond to
issues raised by CFU in connection with the acquisition and
occupation of commercial farms in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to CFU president Tim Henwood, the move was meant to
improve the atmosphere for meaningful dialogue among concerned
parties.
</P>
<P>
CFU pledged on Monday to work with the government to find a
lasting solution to the problems afflicting the country. 
