<HEADLINE> Zambian President Denies Intentions to Impose Sanctions on DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba said the second summit of signatories to the Lusaka peace
accord which ended here Tuesday did not discuss the possibility of
imposing sanctions on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing on Wednesday, Chiluba said during the 18-
hour meeting, which was attended by 10 heads of states, government
officials, representatives of the rebel movements, the United
Nations and the Organization for African Unity, there was no
committee constituted to discuss sanctions on the DRC government
as widely reported in international and local media.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said as opposed to the impression created by media
reports that the summit had collapsed without yielding any results,
a lot of positive results came out of the summit.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed the notion that some heads of states
including DRC President Laurent Kabila abandoned the Lusaka summit
following disagreements among signatories to the Lusaka Summit.
</P>
<P>
"Some heads of state left the summit and the country before the
summit was concluded in the early hours of Tuesday because they
had to meet their other national commitments, while others had to
return home quickly because they did not have clean clothes to
change," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Kabila's departure before the summit was concluded, Chiluba
explained that Kabila had to travel back home because he was
unwell.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba however alluded to the standoff between the DRC
government and the rebels on who was to chair the inter-Congolese
dialog. The DRC government has rejected former Botswanan
president Ketumire Masire as facilitator for the dialog and it
recently locked Masire's offices in Kinshasa accusing him of
siding with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the "sticky" issue of who chairs the internal DRC
dialog was not resolved at the summit and still remained hanging,
awaiting further discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
