<HEADLINE> Nigerian Lawmakers Urged to Confine to Own Responsibilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo has urged members of the country's National Assembly to
confine themselves to their constitutional responsibilities, press
here reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said Tuesday that it is not the responsibilities of
the legislature to saddle itself with the award of contracts,
saying that it would make it become both the executor and judge,
sacrificing the principles of checks and balances the legislature
should be upholding, said the president.
</P>
<P>
It's the first time the president has commented on the matters
relating to the country's top legislature since the Senate
corruption scandal earlier this month, which removed the senate
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo was cautious with words on the top legislature, for
the ties between the two branches of government had been on the
strain in the past months.
</P>
<P>
The president also slammed the legislators' taking of "illegal
and unconstitutional allowances", saying members of the executive,
legislative and judiciary are all public officers, whose action
must be put under public scrutiny. 
</P>
</TEXT>
