<HEADLINE> Drought Eases, Rain Expected in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The drought condition that has
affected Kenya for most part of the year is now easing up and the
short rains are expected in October, according to a source at the
Kenya's Meteorological Department.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Wednesday quoted the source
as saying "due to change in weather conditions in most parts of
the country, indications show that the weather has now reverted
back to normal in the third quarter to the end of the year."
</P>
<P>
He said the rain being experienced in Nakuru town, the capital
of Rift Valley Province in central Kenya, due to the moist Western
Congo air-mass which results in rains in the western and Rift
Valley regions when it blows to the east.
</P>
<P>
However, the water crisis in Kenya's capital Nairobi worsens as
most estates in the city have gone without water for two weeks
running, while others received the water sporadically at night and
in small quantity.
</P>
<P>
In early June, the city council began the water rationing
program in the capital. Residents urged the city council to sink
more boreholes in estates or encouraged residents to sink
boreholes in their residence instead of relying on piped water.
</P>
<P>
Due to a prolonged drought, more than 3 million Kenyans are
facing the famine threat. Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi and the
United Nations World Food Program have appealed to international
community for food aid to the affected Kenyans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
