<DOCNO> XIE20000815.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troop Deployment in Zanzibar not to Influence Elections: Defense Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Ministry of
Defense and National Service has refuted claims by some opposition
parties that the Tanzania People's Defense Forces (TPDF) has
dispatched troops to Zanzibar in a bid to boost the ranks of
supporters of a certain political party for the forthcoming
elections.
</P>
<P>
The official Daily News Wednesday quoted a press release issued
by the ministry as saying that recent troop deployment is intended
to reinforce security in the Indian Ocean Isles, a semi-autonomous
region of Tanzania, during the run-up to the elections scheduled
for October 29.
</P>
<P>
"The army is not involved in politics and therefore does not
support any political party, but will provide defense and security
for all regardless of their political affiliations," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the army will not interfere in the voting activities in
Zanzibar until such a time that it is asked to help when breach of
peace for the people or their property is eminent.
</P>
<P>
While in Zanzibar, said the statement, army personnel, like
other citizens, will participate in the electoral process, but
will cast their votes for the presidential candidates of the
Tanzanian Union government only.
</P>
<P>
"They will not be allowed to vote for the Zanzibar president,
Members of Parliament or Members of the House of Representatives
because the Isles electoral law does not allow any person to
participate in the elections if he or she has not stayed there for
five years."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief of Defense Forces General Robert Mboma
cautioned the military forces Tuesday to keep away from politics
because their responsibility is to defend whatever government to
be elected by the people.
</P>
<P>
The military chief said under the current democratic multiparty
system in Tanzania, the defense forces have no right to
participate in politics except through voting.
</P>
<P>
Political tension has been rising high recently in Zanzibar
since the voting registration exercise started on August 8,
forcing the government under the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (CCM)
to take measures to enhance security in the Isles.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar joined with mainland Tanganyika to form the United
Republic of Tanzania in 1964. But it has its own government and
parliament. It will go to polls in October simultaneously with the
mainland during the second multiparty elections. Zanzibaris have
the right to vote for their own president as well as for a leader
of the Union government.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's CCM, under President Salmin Amour, claimed a narrow
victory over the opposition Civic United Front (CUF) in the 1995
elections, but the CUF questioned the result. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
