<HEADLINE> Uganda Completes Troop Withdrawal From Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 16 (Xinhua) -- The withdrawal of 4,000 Ugandan
soldiers from the town of Buta in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC) has come to an end, Army Spokesman Phinehas Katirima
told Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The withdrawal of personnel has ended and equipment is still
being brought home," said Katirima, adding that the whole exercise
is expected to be completed soon.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers from Buta will be deployed in northern Uganda to
fight remnants of anti-government rebel Lord's Resistance Army.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni last June ordered the withdrawal of
five battalions which had fought in the northeastern Congolese
city of Kisangani in May and June against the Rwandan soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The five battalions moved to Buta after the demilitarization of
Kisangani under the agreement of Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan and Rwandan troops fought each other three times since
last August in Kisangani, the third largest city in the DRC, which
caused heavy civilian casualties. 
</P>
