<HEADLINE> Five People Killed in Mont Blanc Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Five climbers were killed Tuesday
when an avalanche swept through a group of twenty making the
normal Tour Ronde ascent at about 3,800 meters high on Mont Blanc,
head of Val D'Aosta's Alpine rescue unit Giuliano Trucco said
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said the mass of snow and ice hit the climbers at about
midday, and the climbers were French, German and Italian.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the dead were taken to Chamonix in France by
French and Italian Alpine rescue helicopters.
</P>
<P>
All but two of the fifteen injured were also taken to Chamonix.
The two were brought to hospital in Italian northwestern city of
Aosta and released almost at once.
</P>
<P>
Alpine guides said Tuesday's high temperatures seem to have
loosened boulders on top of the Tour Ronde. These then tumbled
down and triggered the avalanche.
</P>
<P>
The normal climb up the Tour Ronde is on the French side of the
mountain. The guides say that in summer, it should only be climbed
in the early morning because of the risk of falling rocks and
avalanches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
