<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stock Markets End Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) - London and Paris stock markets
closed higher Tuesday led by buoyant banks and telecoms, along
with higher oil and tech shares.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index rose 0.9 percent to 6475.5. Computer
chip designer ARM Holdings climbed 4.5 percent while BHM, a maker
of equipment used in fiber-optic networks, rose 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The oil and gas sector added 16 points to the FTSE 100 as Brent
crude futures surged to 10-year highs. Index heavyweight BP Amoco
rose 2.2 percent, while Shell ended 1.4 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks rose on speculation that the industry may
consolidate further after Barclays agreed to buy Woolwich for 8.1
billion U.S. dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
Abbey National added 2.4 percent, Alliance &AMP; Leicester advanced
2.3 percent and Halifax climbed 3.4 percent. Barclays rose 3.1
percent and index heavyweight HSBC Holdings rose 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Outside of the FTSE 100, shares of Oxford BioMedica rocketed 18.
5 percent after the biotechnology firm said it has discovered 23
previously unknown genes that may play a role in cancer, heart
conditions and inflammatory disease.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris added 0.4 percent to 6636.61, with chip
maker STMicroelectronics adding 5.5 percent, to lead the market
higher, and data network operator Equant rising 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax index fell 0.5 percent to 7298.11, with
retailer Metro down almost 4 percent amid concerns the company
faces eviction from Europe's top 50 blue-chip stock index.
</P>
</TEXT>
